(660, 4, '2015-03-29 19:34:05', '2015-03-29 19:34:05', '<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Blog-Image.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-665 size-full" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Blog-Image.png" alt="6 Opportunities in Equity Crowdfunding" width="850" height="700" /></a>\r\n\r\nEquity crowdfunding is proving to be a global phenomenon; it is making way for a brand new sector that is full of new and exciting opportunities for a wide range of stakeholders.\r\n\r\nUnlike other forms of crowdfunding, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equity_crowdfunding">equity crowdfunding</a> is emerging with an entire co-requisite eco-system designed to support all practitioners involved. The sector’s rapid expansion is creating a wide variety of business opportunities.\r\n\r\nEquity crowdfunding portals operate in a way similar to stock exchanges. Indeed, like any stock exchange, a plurality of services are required to support the exchange operators, its investors, the involved securities issuers, and the accompanying equity crowdfunding platforms. A key distinction between traditional stock exchange and equity crowdfunding platforms is in the sheer number of equity portals that are launching around the globe in comparison. As of Q3 of the 2014 fiscal year, <a href="http://ceo.ca/2015/02/04/meet-the-new-ceo-of-minings-first-equity-crowdfunding-platform/">over 540 </a>such equity portals have begun to operate.\r\n\r\nThis rapid growth in the number of these equity crowdfunding platforms has the potential to provide great opportunities to those who have long remained on the sidelines, wondering what they can do to get involved and participate. As the sector emerges, issuing companies and service providers need help locating each other using commonly agreed industry terminologies. Investors need to be confident that they are part of a well-integrated eco-system in order not to feel under-equipped in the face of emerging business opportunities that come with this new crowdfunding platform.\r\n\r\nEquity Crowdfunding currently presents six key opportunities to potential investors and consumers alike:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Vertical Markets</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nWhen equity crowdfunding first launched, it was commonly held that technology companies would be the dominant users of this form of capital raising. Having tracked equity crowdfunding’s scope and momentum as it evolves around the globe, we see a very interesting trend emerging.\r\n\r\nInvestors are moving towards vertically based equity crowdfunding portals.  These equity portals provide investors opportunities in one vertical, with qualified teams capable of building trust and expertise in the deals they eventually to list on equity crowdfunding platforms.\r\n\r\nThe verticals that are gaining traction the fastest are <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/vanessagrout/2014/09/10/move-over-kickstarter-real-estate-equity-crowdfunding-is-catching-on-with-investors/">real estate</a>, <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/brucebooth/2013/12/11/crowdfunding-angels-in-biotech-or-devil-in-the-details/">bio-tech,</a> and consumer goods.  Industry observers who were previously on the sidelines, thinking that equity crowdfunding was confined to technology companies, are now realizing the range of capital raising options available. These opportunities remain, they are multiplying.\r\n\r\nIn 2015, we expect to see more equity crowdfunding portals launching in other verticals such as <a href="http://www.klondikestrike.com/">mining</a>, agriculture, oil &amp; gas, manufacturing, marine industries, automotive industries, Cannabis, restauration, renewable and solar energy, and fashion retailing.\r\n\r\nThe vertical integration embedded in the structure of equity crowdfunding deals are increasing consumer and issuers’ confidence in the quality and resilience of recently listed deals: a sustainable trend that can be banked on.\r\n<ol start="2">\r\n	<li><strong>Cross-Border</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nCross-border equity crowdfunding is now a real and global industry trend. In North America recently, <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/wafu-inc-launches-first-ever-simultaneous-cross-border-equity-crowdfunding-offering/">WAFU </a>(a Canadian company) did a simultaneous equity crowdfunding in Canadian and American securities markets, simultaneously using two different equity crowdfunding portals (<a href="https://circleup.com/">CircleUP</a>, <a href="http://www.theocmx.com/">OCMX</a>).\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.dentons.com/">Dentons</a>, a major international legal advisory player, advised on this deal. It boasts the requisite infrastructure to assist companies in both US and Canadian markets. This has substantial cost-efficiency and savings implications for equity crowdfunding clients who opt to choose this path.\r\n\r\nThis is an ongoing trend in Canada’s legal landscape. Firms in Canada and the United States are now creating equity crowdfunding teams as part of their capital markets practice. First movers are <a href="http://www.egsllp.com/">Ellenoff Grossman &amp; Schole LLP</a>, Seyhavth, <a href="http://www.weirfoulds.com/" target="_blank">Weir Foulds LLP</a>, <a href="http://www.blg.com/" target="_blank">BLG LLP</a>, Baker MacKenzine, with many more to come. This trend benefits issuing companies and investors as they gain a variety of trusted advisors with the expertise to assist in their capital raising efforts via equity crowdfunding.\r\n\r\nParties interested in equity crowdfunding now benefit from more and more advisory firms, accounting, operational consulting, and other specialist service providers extending their services to potential issuers and capital-raising companies.\r\n<ol start="3">\r\n	<li><strong>Partnerships</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIn business, we all understand the value of partnerships. It can be the differentiating factor between a successful fundraising effort and very public flop.\r\n\r\nEquity Crowdfunding is no exception to this longstanding rule. These emerging equity portals are regulated by securities agencies. They will have stringent restrictions on the types of partnerships they can feature. This is to ensure that there are no violations of securities law. There is, however, one type of partnership that equity crowdfunding portals currently favor in this next stage of their evolution.\r\n\r\nEquity portals are looked favorably by private equity groups, venture capital firms, angel investors, and other large corporate financial investors. They focus on the new platform’s two fundamentals in equity crowdfunding: deal flow and talent flow, according to Jason Best at <a href="http://crowdfundcapitaladvisors.com/about-us/our-team/jason-best.html">Crowdfund</a>.\r\n\r\nEquity crowdfunded deals bring these two key investment criterion in a way that is uniquely compatible with these investors’ strategic objectives.\r\n\r\nWe see great examples of these uniquely compatible partnerships with CircleUP; the very first Equity Crowdfunding portal in the USA, which entered into a groundbreaking partnership with Proctor Gamble. To date, CircleUP has helped consumer-focused companies raise more than $US 30Million. It has now gained two additional partners in its efforts, Johnson &amp; Johnson, and Virgin America. This success validates CirclueUp’s team in its choosing this new capital-raising platform.  Ryan (Last Name Missing), CEO of CircleUp showed the entire equity crowdfunding sector that this partnership model works.\r\n\r\nAnother successful example is Israel-based OurCrowd, who partnered with GE Ventures. These happened in the past year, with no sign of relenting. Observers can expect to see more cases of this partnership model to occur as they become industry practice. OurCrowd has helped companies raise $100M US to date.\r\n\r\nSo what do these partnership bring to the equity crowdfunding portal? Recognition, legitimacy, and trust.\r\n<ol start="4">\r\n	<li><strong>Global Portal Expansions</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nEquity Crowdfunding portals are not content with staying in a single listing market. More practitioners are considering locations around the world prior to announcing a deal, a trend that is likely to stay. Equity portals increasingly expand globally by finding broker dealers in multiple countries of their interest, and having them service their particular brand. Equity Portals such as <a href="https://www.crowdcube.com/">CrowdCube</a>, Seedrs, <a href="https://www.ourcrowd.com/" target="_blank">OurCrowd</a>, Invesdor, <a href="klondikestrike.com/" target="_blank">KlondikeStrike</a> are already making these steps in their global expansion.\r\n\r\nThis operational model is preferred by equity crowdfunding platforms as a precursor to their eventual plans to acquire the capacity to raise capital globally and simultaneously, in a few years. This objective also provides tremendous price-discovery opportunities for consumers as they scour the world for the best equity crowdfunding deal.\r\n<ol start="5">\r\n	<li><strong>Secondary Markets</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nPotential investors are often reluctant to commit their scarce capital in companies without some semblance of an exit strategy present. Some element of liquidity must be present to entice investors. This concern is now being addressed as more secondary markets for crowdfunded-equities emerge as a result of the model’s popularity.\r\n\r\nThe United States and Canada now have established secondary markets for these particular equities, allowing for more flexibility and liquidity, along with a third type of exit option for already-committed investors.\r\n<ol start="6">\r\n	<li><strong>Infrastructure</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nEquity crowdfunding’s main operational objective is to optimize its value chain and provide the lowest-cost equity issuing opportunities for investors, portals and issuers alike. Reducing transaction cost across the board is one of this capital-raising model’s key priorities. This directly translates into seamlessly integrated partnerships and lines of operations.\r\n\r\nThe entire eco-system features a seamless infrastructure from A-Z to facilitate the process of equity crowdfunding, from Pre-Raise, During-Raise, to Post-Raise. Compliance and overhead costs are also kept at their very minimum thanks to the rich eco-system of service providers embedded in its operations’ network.\r\n\r\nTechnology is the key factor responsible for equity crowdfunding’s competitive pricing and low-cost operational profile. As such, practitioners are taking advantage of every cost-cutting opportunity made possible by advancements in cloud and data-mining technologies. As a result, equity crowdfunding’s operations will become seamlessly and cost-efficiently global in nature, allowing it to grow as in the industry mainstream as a standard.', '6 Opportunities in Equity Crowdfunding', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', '6-opportunities-in-equity-crowdfunding', '', '', '2015-04-01 13:30:31', '2015-04-01 13:30:31', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=660', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(663, 4, '2015-03-30 21:25:19', '2015-03-30 21:25:19', '', '6 Opportunities in Equity Crowdfunding', '6 Opportunities in Equity Crowdfunding', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', 'blog-2', '', '', '2015-03-30 21:25:48', '2015-03-30 21:25:48', '', 660, 'http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Blog.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(664, 10, '2015-03-31 03:36:18', '2015-03-31 03:36:18', 'Last week, the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) announced a major update to the rules and regulations that currently apply to equity crowdfunding. The announced updates constitute a major step forward for this new crowdfunding method, being considerably less restrictive than existing guidelines as listed in <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/01/61469-the-funding-cap-on-title-iii-retail-crowdfunding-is-pointless/">Title III Equity Crowdfunding</a> of the Jumpstart Our Business Startups Act (<a href="https://www.sec.gov/spotlight/jobs-act.shtml">JOBS Act</a>). The move comes at a great surprise for industry watchers in light of their radical departure from Title III''s <a href="https://www.sec.gov/comments/s7-09-13/s70913-533.pdf">onerous, restrictive, and expensive</a> listing requirements.\r\n\r\nUnder current and expiring regulations, issuers are required to list their Crowdfunding equity offerings in <a href="http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CHRG-113hhrg80819/pdf/CHRG-113hhrg80819.pdf">each and every State nation-wide</a> where they solicited investors, with the expensive <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/03/65007-the-reg-a-bombshell-50m-unaccredited-equity-crowdfunding-title-iv-takes-center-stage/">compliance and filing expenses to boot</a>. No more, starting June 2015, equity crowdfunders will be able to overall raise more, advertise to a wider audience, with better streamlined filing requirements as they become able to pre-empt <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/03/65007-the-reg-a-bombshell-50m-unaccredited-equity-crowdfunding-title-iv-takes-center-stage/">individual State approval</a>.\r\n\r\nThe announced changes also allow issuers to take advantage of more freedom in determining the pace at which they seek financing from public offerings. A startup is now <a href="http://www.dentons.com/~/media/PDFs/Insights/2014/January/SEC_JOBS_Act.pdf">allowed to ease its way from</a> minor Tier I ($20 Millions) public offerings for every 12 months period, to subsequent rounds of heftier Tier II (up to $50 Millions), in a way that in no way precludes them from the more standard initial public offering (IPO). Given the <a href="http://qz.com/205374/tech-ipos-went-from-frenzy-to-fizzle-in-about-a-month/">tepid environment</a> in capital markets as of early 2015 for tech-start-up IPOs, with many cancelled or <a href="http://qz.com/204779/boxs-highly-anticipated-ipo-should-hit-in-late-may/">flopped</a>, it is now easier for issuers to test market appetite <a href="http://www.sec.gov/news/pressrelease/2015-49.html#.VRnusFzqY20">prior to major listing</a> announcements and legal, regulatory, expenses.\r\n\r\nHere are six key take-always you should be aware of as <a href="http://www.sec.gov/news/pressrelease/2015-49.html#.VRnjjpPF_T1">Regulation A+</a> comes into effect in June 2015:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong> Startup companies can now equity crowdfund up to $20 or $50 millions per year.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2013/12/28633-sec-approves-new-rules-regulation/">Under the new incoming regulation</a>, startup companies will be able to raise up to either $20 millions under Tier I of Regulation A+ or $50 millions under Tier II upon submitting two years of audited, or simply reviewed, financial statements. They will additionally be able to host subsequent rounds of crowdfunding every 12 months, without meeting a particular notional cumulative cap, provided that they continue to meet <a href="http://www.sec.gov/rules/final/2015/33-9741.pdf">NASAA Coordinated Review</a> standards.\r\n<ol start="2">\r\n	<li><strong> Investment companies are not allowed to equity crowdfund under the new rules. </strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe <a href="http://www.sec.gov/news/pressrelease/2015-49.html#.VRnusFzqY20">changes</a> coming to applicable equity crowdfunding rounds exclude private equity funds, hedge funds, and venture capital funds, investment companies in short, from taking advantage of this new way to raise startup capital from the public. This is a welcome development, as it prevents deep-pocketed funds from crowding out smaller seekers of the general public’s demand for crowdfunded startup <a href="http://www.sec.gov/news/pressrelease/2015-49.html#.VRnjjpPF_T1">shares</a>.\r\n<ol start="3">\r\n	<li><strong> No restrictions on the advertisement of offerings.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nOne of the most significant aspects of the crowdfunding rules to come makes it <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/03/65007-the-reg-a-bombshell-50m-unaccredited-equity-crowdfunding-title-iv-takes-center-stage/">legal for a startup company to advertise</a> its share offerings to the general public, without restrictions, in mainstream media. This rule means that for many companies, you can expect Twitter, Facebook, television, and other major social media platforms to feature advertisements for equity crowdfunding shares as new products get announced.\r\n<ol start="4">\r\n	<li><strong> No restrictions on who can invest, no proof of income required from investors.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe large majority of public equity offerings, offerings of shares for free public distribution and exchange, <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2013/12/28633-sec-approves-new-rules-regulation/">were under strict limit</a> as to who could invest. Households with a combined income of $200,000 or a net worth of $1 million and accredited investors were the only ones allowed to participate. Under the <a href="http://www.sec.gov/rules/final/2015/33-9741.pdf">Regulation A+</a>, investments as small as $100 are possible, provided that interested investors can show that the funds are less or equal to the higher of either 10% of their net income or 10% of their declared net-worth. No additional paperwork are required to prove specific investors’ incomes.\r\n<ol start="5">\r\n	<li><strong> No disclosure requirements for Tier I &amp; annual disclosure filings for Tier II rounds.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nTier I offerings, those raising up to $20 Millions will only have to show reviewed financial statements. Meanwhile, Tier II offerings, up to $50 Million dollars, will be required to file annual disclosures, semi-annual reports, and current reports. These are respectively simply mini-equivalents of the better-known 10-K, 10-Q, and Form 8-K filings for mainstream listed companies.\r\n<ol start="6">\r\n	<li><strong> Free transfer, fungibility of all securities issued during equity crowdfunding rounds.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nInvestors in equity crowdfunded rounds will be able to freely buy and re-sell shares acquired during crowdfunding rounds under <a href="http://www.sec.gov/news/pressrelease/2015-49.html#.VRnjjpPF_T1">Regulation A+</a>. This change in regulation means that observers can expect a vibrant secondary market for equity crowdfunding’s shares, adding an element of liquidity to the new instrument.\r\n\r\nThe new set of crowdfunding rules announced by the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) on March 25th is proving to be a bombshell. It paves the way for the creation of new venture exchanges for shares resulting from this new way to raise capital to a much larger set of investors. It should altogether make it easier for emerging startups to circumvent venture capital’s storied gatekeepers, and take their business cases directly to an eager mass public.', 'What Will Crowdfunding in 2015 Look Like?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', 'what-will-crowdfunding-in-2015-look-like', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=664', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(665, 4, '2015-03-31 17:18:19', '2015-03-31 17:18:19', '', '6 Opportunities in Equity Crowdfunding', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', 'blog-image', '', '', '2015-03-31 17:18:45', '2015-03-31 17:18:45', '', 660, 'http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Blog-Image.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(666, 10, '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Crowdfunding is all the rage in the first quarter of 2015, with many leading Venture Capital firms putting their money on the new industry they see as the future of finance; a democratized one at that. The industry is not new; however, as musicians in the 1980s commonly used its capital raising power to <a href="http://blogs.wsj.com/accelerators/2014/09/30/sandeep-sood-the-rise-of-crowdfunding/">draw a living wage from fans and friends</a>, hoping to make it to the big entertainment business leagues. With the onset of the financial crisis in 2007, the charitable sector suffered a draw-down in available philanthropic donations amidst a cash crunch. This led more creative, grassroots, initiatives such as <a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=2&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCoQFjAB&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.kiva.org%2Fpress&amp;ei=2_gbVbPeDreKsQTu94J4&amp;usg=AFQjCNEG_lS1UUMWSfZYDxDCSWVbidn1wg&amp;sig2=xlLM1m3JaW7dnM5zA8AZnQ&amp;bvm=bv.89744112,d.cWc">Kiva Microfinance and Indiegogo</a> to resort to crowdfunded donations to lend money to viable causes, or provide in-kind goods in exchange for some startup capital.\r\n\r\nThis trend was picked up by plenty of seed-stage companies, to the extent that by 2010-2011, crowdfunding managed to raise <a href="http://blog.clarity.fm/clarity-exclusive-crowdfundings-epic-growth-infographic/">a whopping $1.5 billion</a> from widespread supporters and backers worldwide. The trend is going strong, spawning a whole industry with service providers, as The World Bank Group forecasts that the global crowdfunding market is set to expand into a <a href="http://www.infodev.org/crowdfunding">$96 billion market by 2025</a>. What''s driving this boom in crowdfunding? The confluence of trends in capital markets, financial regulation, and in crowdfunding economics'' unique fit with demand and supply-side incentives on the part of its stakeholders in the aftermath of a severe economic recession.\r\n\r\nThe 2008 financial crisis is the single greatest cause of the emergence of crowdfunding as an increasingly established standard of capital-raising. As most know, the financial sector''s risky financial engineering led to taxpayer-funded bank bailouts and a deep-seated loss of confidence in the industry as a whole. Risk took a back seat to tough regulation and excessive prudence on the part of the largest holders of capital: investment banks, private equity and hedge funds, and corporate treasuries. This immediately translated into a tepid market for IPOs and higher overall requirements for start-ups looking to raise capital. <a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=5&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CD4QFjAE&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.foxbusiness.com%2Fmarkets%2F2014%2F02%2F28%2Fsquare-ipo-postponed-indefinitely%2F&amp;ei=SfsbVdfsHajlsAT22YLoDQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNGJUYR5J1Zs2O9ZATqLjGJ68WICCw&amp;sig2=WFJh1SXz3Ja7rwRBAaSk3A&amp;bvm=bv.89744112,d.cWc">Square, King Digital Entertainment</a> (the famous maker of the candy crush and farm heroes sagas), and plenty other companies saw IPOs <a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=2&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCUQFjAB&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.vcpost.com%2Farticles%2F19437%2F20131209%2Fuk-mobile-games-maker-king-delays-ipo-due-candy-crush.htm&amp;ei=SfsbVdfsHajlsAT22YLoDQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNEoskQauQe4yWTt3GkJ8uF_9X7Dcg&amp;sig2=5rNSlSG-xlda_J-7r0SkVQ&amp;bvm=bv.89744112,d.cWc">delayed, postponed indefinitely</a> or performing poorly in the markets versus expectations. Technology start-up founders and VC stage companies were going to have to look elsewhere for their capital-raising needs.\r\n\r\nWhat''s more, the Dodd-Frank Act and its accompanying suite of new financial regulations made it harder for typical pre-2008 risk appetite to remain in the markets. It led to a structural shift in the investing world, one that pushed risk towards it’s most discriminating players, Venture Capital firms. Investment Banks were encouraged to spin off, or hive off, risk-taking entities. Private Equity funds were encouraged to behave more like Investment Banks, as evident in preeminent private equity house the Blackstone Group''s <a href="http://www.forbes.com/pictures/fjle45iegh/no-1-the-blackstone-group/">creation of an IB arm</a>, for example. Hedge Funds were either divested-from by their institutional investors who jumped to infrastructure investing and real assets or overall sat the market out in sovereign debt-related, long -term instruments. All of these trends sucked capital out of conventional markets for venture capital funding and led venture capital firms to ask for more expensive terms in general. VCs also became more selective, in order to respond to the shift in risk pricing by the market.\r\n\r\nFrom then on, startup companies met with increasing success, as a result of improvements in <a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=3&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CC4QFjAC&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.pressreader.com%2Fthailand%2Fbangkok-post%2F20150327%2F282071980399258%2FTextView&amp;ei=0gYcVY3mO-nHsQT5qYGQAQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNGDdArLYRlwZlxql6ug6u7LlFD1iA&amp;sig2=4wv9mDk_1ByVs0-QtiYzhw&amp;bvm=bv.89744112,d.cWc">financial technology</a> (fintech) investment such as mobile payments, online purchases, and savvier use of social media. In order to meet the more demanding terms of Venture Capital investors, or to altogether sideline them, founders began to resort to crowdfunding campaigns. This in order to demonstrate the sheer level of interest their business models were attracting; a move that gave them leveraged with VC negotiations.\r\n\r\nThe creation of the Jumpstart Our Business Startups Act (JOBS Act) in 2012, was a key watershed moment in the rise of crowdfunding. It allowed a wider set of investors to receive shares in startups in exchange for some invested capital. No, longer were grassroots contributors restricted to advanced deliveries of goods or quirky gifts, in terms of what they could receive from capital raising companies. Title II, III, and Regulation D of the JOBS Act, allowed companies to generally <a href="http://techcrunch.com/2014/10/17/one-year-into-title-ii-of-the-jobs-act/">solicit stock-based investment</a> into their companies from individuals not affiliated or aware of given companies'' business case.\r\n\r\nThis change in regulation resulted in an increase from $1.5 billion to more than $5.1 billion in 2013.This is exemplified in Pebble watch''s ability to <a href="http://venturebeat.com/2012/04/12/pebble-smartwatch/">raise $1.2 million in 30 hours</a> on the back of these regulatory changes. What''s more, the JOBS Act was further amended to increase the maximum amount that listing firms are allowed to raise, in this case between $20 million to $50 million dollars. This bombshell preceded the growth in the number of equity crowdfunding platforms around the world in the 290s around the world, a sign of the method becoming a global standard option for pre-VC startup finance. This drastically affected the deal economics for both issuers, their accompanying ecosystem of service providers, and early backers of early-stage companies.\r\n\r\nFor investors, the resounding success of the Facebook Inc. IPO''s early supporters like Peter Thiel, who invested $5 million leading to an IPO valuation of $104 billion, combined with risk-aversion from the financial crisis, made the business case of backing crowdfunding platforms. The JOBS Act''s Regulation A+ <a href="http://www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.sec.gov%2Fnews%2Fpressrelease%2F2015-49.html%23.VRwJ5fnF_eI&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNES0Aa_uaTTFIavvtF7_uo4RZR8RA">now restricts</a> private equity, venture capital funds, and other investors from investing in crowdfunding. This creates incentives for them to get on the side of the emerging platforms, and to use prior success as an investment criteria for later Series A and B venture capital rounds. What''s more, as the team at <a href="http://seventysixcapital.com/">Seventy Six Capital</a> argues, for investment bankers and investment managers the winner-take-all nature of the crowdfunding business is sure to lead to consolidations with <a href="http://fortune.com/2014/04/17/why-investors-are-pouring-millions-into-crowdfunding/">plenty of rooms for mergers</a>.\r\n\r\nFor service providers and issuers, the rapid emergence of growth hackers and social media strategists, legal due-diligence experts, and other pre-crowdfund requirements are leading to an explosion in the size and scope of equity crowdfunding. This trend is reinforcing the dominance of the method as a standard option for capital-raising worldwide. Meaning here that the industry''s rapid growth and its series of marked successes is a bellwether of the future of venture capital finance. This was evident in Pebble''s successful announcement-related crowdfunding just as Apple was announcing its new Apple Smartwatch to skeptical industry observers.  The previously cited study by the World Bank group and other analysts see the equity crowdfunding growing to almost three times the size of today''s venture capital industry. This might be one lesson learned from the financial crisis, a major gift indeed.', 'Who is Driving the Crowd?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=666', 0, 'post', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(668, 10, '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Equity crowdfunding is still a foreign concept for many individuals. To understand why equity crowdfunding is emerging on a global level, we must first recognize the financing inefficiencies that hinder startups and investors alike.\r\n\r\nEarly-stage startups have traditionally acquired necessary capital from two streams: equity financing and crowdfunding platforms.\r\n\r\nVenture capitalists and angel investors are the main parties that contribute capital in exchange for equity. With few investors providing very large investments, equity financing raises the key issue of accessibility to a larger pool of investors.\r\n\r\nPlatforms like <a href="https://www.kickstarter.com/">Kickstarter</a> solve the problem of limited investors but open up another can of worms. Take for instance <a href="https://www.oculus.com/">Oculus VR</a>, which raised over <a href="https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/1523379957/oculus-rift-step-into-the-game">$2.4 million</a> on Kickstarter. Initial supporters received simple gifts and rewards rather than equity for their investments, and thus were subsequently left on the outside looking in when Facebook acquired Oculus VR for <a href="http://techcrunch.com/2014/07/21/facebooks-acquisition-of-oculus-closes-now-official/">$2 billion</a>.\r\n\r\nTraditional methods of raising capital limit investor accessibility and offer no opportunity for incredible returns. These problems have paved the way for the emergence of equity crowdfunding, a revolutionary process that democratizes early-stage investment.\r\n\r\nThe premise of equity crowdfunding is as simple as its name; individuals invest in startup companies in return for equity. Equity crowdfunding’s expected growth can be attributed to the following factors.\r\n<h1>REGULATORY DEVELOPMENT</h1>\r\nBack in 2013, Title II of the Jumpstart Our Business Startups (JOBS) <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2013/09/23/the-crowdfunders-guide-to-general-solicitation-title-ii-of-the-jobs-act/">Act</a> was fully implemented and restricted crowdfunding access to “accredited investors”. Under the Act, “accredited investors” were classified as individuals with at least $1 million in net worth or an annual salary exceeding $200 000. This classification proved to be a huge stumbling block, as everyday investors were still unable to seize equity investment opportunities.\r\n\r\nVery recently, the Securities and Exchange Commission has lifted the barrier preventing non-accredited investors from participating in equity crowdfunding. Title IV rulings provide companies with two alternatives to raise either $20 million or $50 million in 12 months, both of which will be open to accredited and non-accredited investors.\r\n\r\nOfferings in the <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/03/65007-the-reg-a-bombshell-50m-unaccredited-equity-crowdfunding-title-iv-takes-center-stage/">first tier</a> (raising $20 million) will not be subjected to state pre-emption nor required to complete formal audits. <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/03/64990-final-rules-for-title-iv-of-the-jobs-act-to-include-state-pre-emption-but-for-tier-2-only/">Tier II</a> allows for blue sky law pre-emption and necessitates annual financial audits and reports. Most businesses are expected to adopt Tier II, as the ability to pre-empt state law is a significant game-changer. Previously, companies had to register their offers in every single state; blue sky law pre-emption circumvents this unnecessary hassle by offering an administratively efficient method of raising capital. The trend of growing consulting, legal, and accounting service firms in the equity crowdfunding space will only efficiently streamline the process.\r\n\r\nTo protect non-accredited, less experienced investors, SEC will enforce a cap of 10% of their annual income to minimize the risk of investing in startups (75% fail according to this <a href="http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390443720204578004980476429190">study</a>).\r\n\r\nIn light of the recent regulatory developments, donation-based crowdfunding platforms like <a href="https://www.indiegogo.com/">IndieGoGo</a> are considering a <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/03/65063-indiegogo-is-poised-to-move-into-equity-crowdfunding/">move</a> into the equity crowdfunding space, a harbinger of more platforms adopting an equity-focused model. The trend towards accessibility will be a key driver of the growth of equity crowdfunding platforms.\r\n<h1>ACCESS TO ALTERNATIVE INVESTMENTS</h1>\r\nInvestors looking for high returns outside of public markets can now turn to alternative investments via equity crowdfunding. Previously restricted to accredited investors, private companies and attractive funds are trending towards equity crowdfunding platforms. A few opportunities include:\r\n\r\n<strong>Real Estate – </strong>Real Estate Investment Trusts were unattractive to the general investor because there was no option to invest small sums. Platforms such as <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2014/09/50779-hbs-prodigy-network-democratizing-real-estate-investment/">Prodigy Network</a> and <a href="http://www.bkreader.com/2015/03/whos-street-our-street/">Our Street</a> are democratizing real estate investment for as little as $10 000.\r\n\r\n<strong>Hedge Funds</strong> – Similar to REITS, hedge funds were largely inaccessible to investors with limited resources. This industry is now open to disruption, as some platforms (<a href="http://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2014/11/17/sliced-investing-gets-2-million-for-its-online-hedge-fund-investing-platform/">Sliced Investing</a>) offer lower fees (0.5%-1% annually), increased transparency, and minimal investments (starting from $20 000).\r\n\r\n<strong>Private Equity</strong> – Becoming a Limited Partner in a private equity fund is a major financial hurdle requiring over $1 million in investments. The launch of <a href="http://blogs.wsj.com/privateequity/2015/02/13/investx-brings-crowdfunding-to-private-equity-deals/">InvestX</a> brings equity crowdfunding to private equity deals. With a minimum investment of $2 500, individuals can now access private equity deals at a huge discount.\r\n\r\nIt is quite clear that equity crowdfunding opens many doors to alternative investments. Look for a trend of more funds and companies taking this route to raise money in an efficient manner.\r\n<h1>GLOBAL CROWDFUNDING</h1>\r\nThe beauty of equity crowdfunding platforms lies in its freedom to operate beyond a single listing market. Cross-border equity crowdfunding has already begun to materialize, with Canadian company <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/wafu-inc-launches-first-ever-simultaneous-cross-border-equity-crowdfunding-offering/">WAFU Inc</a> raising funds from both Canadian (<a href="https://www.optimizecapitalmarkets.com/">Optimize Capital Markets</a>) and American (<a href="https://circleup.com/">CircleUp</a>) portals to seize the advantages of financial gains and liquidity.\r\n\r\nInternational legal advisory firms (<a href="http://www.dentons.com/">Dentons</a>) are also becoming involved, advising on cross-border deals to improve efficiency and reduce costs for crowdfunding clients. The formation of equity crowdfunding teams in many law firms anticipates an increase in demand for raising capital globally.\r\n\r\nCreating a global presence would reduce information asymmetry between countries; investors would be able to identify the best investment opportunities. Technological advancements in the cloud and data-mining fields will only continue to cut extraneous costs from raising capital and support the infrastructure required to expand globally.\r\n<h1>CLOSING THOUGHTS</h1>\r\nRecent regulatory developments have catalyzed the growth of equity crowdfunding portals. Although providing the general investor, the opportunity to invest has been widely celebrated, a few skeptics such as Mark Cuban express <a href="http://blogmaverick.com/2015/03/04/why-this-tech-bubble-is-worse-than-the-tech-bubble-of-2000/">concerns</a> over inexperienced investors contributing to the tech bubble. Setting all speculation aside, we can observe the indisputable fact that equity crowdfunding platforms have streamlined the process of raising capital, removing previous inefficiencies and opening investment opportunities to everyday investors.', 'What is to Account for the Rise in Equity Crowdfunding?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=668', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(669, 4, '2015-05-27 21:12:00', '2015-05-27 21:12:00', 'Equity crowdfunding as an industry has grown from an annual $1.5 billion raised in 2011, to a predicted annual total of nearly $11 billion in 2015. What''s more studies by the World Bank Group predicts the industry''s expansion into an industry annually raising up to $96 billion, overall set rise to almost three-times the size of today''s venture capital industry. What''s more 291 such equity crowdfunding platforms exist at this time, with more service providers in legal and marketing work, to cite a few, inbound for the new platform. With all the buzz about equity crowdfunding, how many investors know what the term "pre-crowd" means? The answer to this should indicate whether you''re ready, as an investor or issuer, to seriously consider the option.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_735" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Pre-Crowd.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-735" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Pre-Crowd-300x250.png" alt="Define: Pre Crowd" width="300" height="250" /></a> What is pre-crowd[/caption]\r\n\r\nSo what does pre-crowd refer to and why does it matter?  Pre-crowd is short for pre-crowdfunding. It is the first stage of the three principal stages a company goes through when raising capital via equity crowdfunding. They sport very intuitive names, as the "Pre"- stage, the "During"- stage, and the "Post"- stage.  Each of these stages involved in equity crowdfunding come with a requisite set of required legwork. Meeting these requirements is essential for a capital raising round, via crowdfunding, to successfully occur without major self-defeating future liabilities.\r\n\r\nThe "Pre-crowd" stage is that stage during which all of the preparations for a successful crowdfunding round take place. During this sub-stage startups enlist a number of advisors, service providers, and the requisite technologies to accelerate your way through the crowdfunding stage smoothly.\r\n\r\nAt the pre-crowd stage, there is a wide variety of service providers and supporting businesses that are hoping to utilize equity crowdfunding as a means to raise capital for their business. These services distinguish themselves in terms of the timing during which they become useful. The Pre-crowd stage would, for example, feature lawyers and due-diligence companies required to ensure that a company''s efforts satisfy all SEC-related compliance and filing needs. It would also include public relations advisors and crisis management specialists who would help with the messaging and marketing end of the offering as it might be perceived.\r\n\r\nThe During- stage, involves the actual platform on which individual companies chose to list and publicize their offer. It might also involve IT services used to manage any technical issue encountered during the process of leveraging social media for payments purposes. In the same vogue, mobile payment service providers and banking platforms must monitor the logistics of monetary commitment as the crowdfunding round proceeds. Typically, operations management specialists are required to reconcile the symphony of processes at play. These efforts are similar to the way an investment bank''s trading floor, compliance, risk management, and investor relations teams might go about coordinating an initial public offering.\r\n\r\nIn the same vogue, the Post- stage would likely involve public relations managers to make sure there is no unexpected development of the company''s story in the immediate aftermath of a crowdfunding round. Such an unpredictability might endanger said company''s changes of progressing towards further capital-raising rounds; especially as they begin to involve the public markets and other institutional investors.\r\n\r\nHere is a breakdown of the typical types of service providers involved from previous transactions. They come in two main types, business elements and public relations elements. For business elements involved in preparing a pre-crowd stage, companies will require a full business plan before all else. Without a way to communicate your company''s vision, there is very little chance that equity-based investors, or even the founding team, will understand the company''s value proposition. Part of this appeal via your business case involves your team or the startup in question presenting audited or reviewed financial statements.\r\n\r\nNext comes your estimated projections company projections; this gives potential investors a sense of your grasp of the realities of your likely path to an IPO.\r\n\r\nAfter this step, background checks on officers, directors, and some major shareholders, are required to ensure that the issuing team and its management can deliver on the business project on behalf of incoming investors. If background checks yield potential pitfalls in management,  corporate searches are in order. These guarantee that in the short-to-medium term the team receiving shareholder capital will be well sourced and equipped to deliver on the startup''s growth strategy.\r\n\r\nAfter the fundamentals are taken care of in terms of business processes and team-building, public relations is the next critical area for pre-crowd firms to cover as a base. The firm''s social media footprint should be revised and tailored for the company''s next steps in terms of publicity. It is also crucial for the issuing firm to have a public relations strategy overall, as strategic planning is one of the major preventive methods when it comes to reputational risk. Since crowdfunding amounts to banking on a young company''s reputation and hype, this has material consequences and must be a priority. Finally, anyone who has seen Kickstarter, for example, in action while raising funds online, sees that the production quality of their videos if always professional and clearly articulated, and free of double talk. These are key precautions to take during a company''s pre-crowd stage.\r\n\r\nMany simply assume that they can just go to a crowdfunding site and raise money online given the brilliance of their particular business case.  What they fail to realize is that equity crowdfunding portals turn down a large majority of applicants.  They do so because of how frequently unprepared company attempt raise funds from a discriminating public.  Equity portals are required to abide by securities regulations, and they list these clearly on their portals. It is, therefore, more of a privilege  for a company to list successfully on one of these portals. It is vital that startups looking to raise funds use the appropriate service providers.\r\n\r\nAt a minimum, you should be looking at 90 days preparation prior to going live on an equity crowdfunding portal. Watch for my next piece on the topic of how to prepare for crowdfunding.\r\n\r\n@JasonFutko', 'We know equity crowdfunding, but what is "pre-crowd"?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'know-equity-crowdfunding-pre-crowd', '', '', '2015-05-28 16:14:54', '2015-05-28 16:14:54', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=669', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(672, 11, '2015-04-12 15:49:52', '2015-04-12 15:49:52', 'Regulators, particularly securities regulators, are normally a conservative and risk averse lot, generally preferring fraud prevention to economic efficiency.  However sometimes they can come up with some brilliant pieces of economically empowering regulation, particularly when pushed by the political powers that be and when faced with the prospect of a challenging national economic environment.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://cdn.crowdfundinsider.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/SEC-Commissioners-too.png"><img class="alignright  wp-image-65013" src="http://cdn.crowdfundinsider.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/SEC-Commissioners-too-600x292.png" alt="SEC Commissioners too" width="392" height="191" /></a>This is what happened in the United States on March 25, 2015, when the <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/03/65019-title-iv-of-the-jobs-act-final-rules-document/" target="_blank">SEC finally enacted the amendment to Regulation A</a>(commonly known as Regulation A+), which the SEC had been legally and politically mandated to enact by Congress since 2012 under <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/03/65172-fact-sheet-regulation-a-title-iv-of-the-jobs-act/" target="_blank">Title IV of the JOBS Act</a>.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/03/65172-fact-sheet-regulation-a-title-iv-of-the-jobs-act/" target="_blank">The new Regulation A+</a> is brilliant because it recognizes and finally attempts to resolve some of the issues that in my view have previously prevented improved access to adequate amounts of reasonably priced equity capital for small companies in the United States:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Capital raising is expensive and entails large amount of fixed costs (underwriting fees, legal fees, accounting fees, among others).  When the size of the offering is too small, this can represent an uneconomically large portion of the capital raised. Regulation A+ addresses this point by;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>increasing the annual amount that can be privately raised by a company under the exemption from $5 million to $20 million (under Tier 1) or to $50 million (Tier 2); and</li>\r\n	<li>increasing the amount that can be invested by individuals to (i) 5% of that individual’s income or net worth below $100k, or (ii) 10% of that individual’s income or net worth above $100k (up to a maximum investment amount of $100k), with no maximum for accredited investors;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://cdn.crowdfundinsider.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/A-.png"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-65196" src="http://cdn.crowdfundinsider.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/A-.png" alt="A +" width="345" height="322" /></a>The development of secondary markets for the resale of privately placed securities (which is crucial for individual investor liquidity), requires proper initial and continuing periodic disclosure and the freely tradable securities.  Regulation A+ addresses this point by:</li>\r\n	<li>Requiring the filing of a publicly available “Offering Circular” (complying with Form 1-A) with the SEC at least 48 hours prior to the first sale;</li>\r\n	<li>Requiring companies to furnish investors with audited financial statements for the two  (2) most recent fiscal years prepared in accordance with Regulation S-X (US GAAP for US companies) or in accordance with international financial reporting standards (IFRS for Canadian Companies);</li>\r\n	<li>Requiring the filing of annual reports with the SEC under Form 1-K within 120 days of the end of the fiscal year, and semi-annual reports with the SEC under Form 1-SA within 90 calendar days after the end of the first six month period; and</li>\r\n	<li>Making the securities placed under Regulation A+ freely tradable (i.e., not restricted securities).</li>\r\n	<li>Small companies should not be forced to into becoming a public reporting company simply because they successfully raise equity capital from a large number of small investors.  Regulation A+ achieves this by exempting securities placed under. Regulation A+ from the Rule 12(g) Exchange Act requirement that they become public reporting company if they end up with more than 2000 shareholders of record (or more than 500 non-accredited investors), provided that they keep a registered transfer agent, complies with continuing disclosure requirements, and does not have a public float in excess of U.S.$75 million or revenues of more than U.S.$50 million</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a href="http://cdn.crowdfundinsider.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Canada-Equity-Crowdfunding.png"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-27009" src="http://cdn.crowdfundinsider.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Canada-Equity-Crowdfunding.png" alt="Canada Equity Crowdfunding" width="286" height="298" /></a>The developments brought about by Regulation A+ are <em>groundbreaking.</em>\r\n\r\nIn Canada, absent a legal mandate from elected politicians (like the JOBS Act) provincial regulators have lacked the pressure needed to push them to enact more economically effective legislation.  So far the best that they have been able to come up with after several years of work is Multilateral Instrument 45-108 (Crowdfunding) which although useful, falls way short of the legal framework needed for the development of real private capital markets in Canada.\r\n\r\nMI 45-108, which has not yet even been accepted by all of provincial securities regulators, falls way short in several respects:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>It limits the amount that can be raised by a company to $1.5 million per year.  This creates a capital raising system that results in unnecessarily high transactional costs of capital (probably 20%+ amount raised), which will affect amounts invested and future company growth, and hence employment and economic growth;</li>\r\n	<li>It limits the amount that can be invested by an individual in any one company to $2,500 per year. This creates small companies that will be very difficult to administer, because at offering sizes of $1.5 million, 45-108 funded companies will end up having almost 600 shareholders, making it much more difficult and expensive for them to raise capital from and to service and communicate with that many investors;</li>\r\n	<li>It fails to make 45-108 securities freely tradable, thereby preventing the development of a secondary market and making it much more difficult for individual investors to be able to exit from their investment;.</li>\r\n	<li>It fails to address the consequences of 45-108 funded companies ceasing to be private issuers in Canada (i.e., acquiring more than 50 shareholders).  Currently having more than 50 shareholders will result in a company ceasing to qualify for various private issuer exemptions, the loss of which can have serious negative consequences.  For example the loss of the non-reporting issuer exemption under Section 4.9 of MI 62-104  will make any subsequent private M&amp;A exit all the more difficult or unlikely for 45-108 crowdfunded companies.  Making M&amp;A exits more difficult for 45-108 crowdfunded companies will make it more difficult for individual investors to realize any profit or return of capital from their investments.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCanadian politicians need to realize that stimulating small business growth (the job engine of all modern economies) necessitates easier and cheaper access to equity capital than currently being proposed by MI 45-108 and therefore that they need to step up the pressure on provincial regulators to enact additional crowdfunding regulations to match U.S. Regulation A+.', 'Time for Regulators to Step-Up: Canada Needs Crowdfunding Regulations to Match US Reg A+', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'time-for-regulators-to-step-up-canada-needs-crowdfunding-regulations-to-match-us-reg-a', '', '', '2015-04-12 15:50:42', '2015-04-12 15:50:42', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=672', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(674, 10, '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'This spring on May 5<sup>th</sup>, CrowdfundBeat is hosting what is sure to be one of the largest gatherings of Canadian practitioners, service providers, platform specialists, and other capital-raising companies involved the booming equity crowdfunding industry. The event, called the Canadian Crowdfunding Symposium, will be an exceptionally well timed and in-depth opportunity for Canada’s leading experts on the regulation, financial infrastructure, and company logistics, to discuss how to move forward in light of major policy announcements made by regulatory institutions and leading companies in the larger United States venture capital and startup capital raising market during the first quarter of 2015.\r\n\r\nJust a few days ago, the United States Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) announced a bombshell of a regulatory innovation in the world of fundraising. The unexpected Regulation A+, as it is referred to, of the JOBS Act, opened the floodgates for what many see as the next stage in the story of Venture Capital and startup fundraising. Indeed, US regulators officially accepted the practice of equity crowdfunding as a standard step in the process during which a company graduates from seed-funding to the eventual Initial Public Offering (IPO) rounds.\r\n\r\nAmerican startups are now allowed to equity crowdfunding subsequent rounds of $20 million, or $50 million, depending the type of regulatory disclosure regime they best prefer. What’s more, there are no limits to how many consecutive yearly rounds of capital-raising a startups can feasibly seek capital from the public. American investors will be able to invest amounts equivalent to 10% of either their total net worth, or their annual salaries, depending on which is larger. What does this mean in the context of this year’s upcoming annual Canadian Crowdfunding Summit?\r\n\r\nSimilar changes to announced SEC rulers are expected in the Canadian capital-raising sector, many of the attendees will actually be legal practitioners and regulatory analysts who will discuss changes likely to be announced in the coming months. Many often complain about the lack of venture capital funding availability in Toronto, Vancouver, and Montreal, compared to Silicon Valley equivalents; these announced American changes will likely spell easier seed-funding methods available for Canadian startups. Official Canadian crowdfunding regulation are still pending, prospective attendees to CrowdfundBeat 2015 can therefore expect to be a few step ahead of the mainstream Canadian investor in terms of their ability to take advantage of maple-themed capital raising options.\r\n\r\nThe caliber of speakers and panelists for this year’s conference look especially promising, a full spectrum of the equity crowdfunding industry’s main stakeholders will be present to engage with prospective capital-raisers and service providers alike. The expected speakers’ line-up features partners at major Canadian firms such as Cassels Brock &amp; Blackwell LLP, with noted specialisms in corporate and securities law, with additional emphasis on the complexities appending to registration requirements for dealers and advisers in equity-raising rounds. What’s more, key players in the Canadian context offering equity crowdfunding platforms for the industry’s eco-system infrastructure for stakeholders’ benefits are expected to contribute useful listing insights for interested companies. For example, KoreConX’s CEO, Oscar Joffre, will address the attendees on what it takes to support capital raisers during the pre-, the “during”, and the “post” crowdfunding stages of an EC round. Attendees will also benefit from practical advice from leading American crowdfunding-experienced platforms, especially in terms of the plenty of available industry best-practices and lessons obtained from recent equity crowdfunding rounds.\r\n\r\nThe Crowdfunding Annual Summit will be particularly useful this year because it will offer companies and startups interested in seeking the equity crowdfunding route with the basic requirements and opportunities in the Canadian market. Mingling with other interested companies attending, under the purview of the Equity Crowdfunding Alliance of Canada (ECFA Canada)’s savvy intermediation efforts to improve cohesion and collaboration in the booming industry, should prove to be a value-added opportunity for attendees and speaker alike.\r\n\r\nOne other key factor that is expected to emerge from this meeting of prospective Canadian equity crowdfunding practitioners, is the extent of input that that the Ontario Securities Commission will receive ahead of formulating EC regulation north of the border. A key issue that will get special attention on the Summit’s agenda bears on what should be the difference, going forward, between the previously standard practice of perks-based, or gift-based, crowdfunding, and the new option for investors to acquire shares in the companies they support. This change has momentous implications for Canadians venture-specific firms and Canadian Securities law.\r\n\r\nGiven the level of complexity involved in distinguishing between the much larger American market’s experience and the Canadian landscape to come, it is clear that the Summit provides an opportunity to gain a 360-degrees range of insights into just how a startup can successfully manage a round of equity crowdfunding. What’s more, for those aiming to support or further engage the fast-growing industry, there will be a feast of insights available on the changing nature of startup fundraising in the Canadian capital markets landscape.', 'Canadian Investors and Startups Convene to Discuss Future of Crowdfunding Regulation', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=674', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(675, 13, '2015-06-06 22:05:18', '2015-06-06 22:05:18', 'At KoreConX, we do our best to do precisely what our name implies: we make the pieces fit by connecting <em>you</em> with the core understanding you need to make informed decisions about your business. That’s why we have created the “Fundamental Facts” series: a collection of articles geared at guiding you through the fundamentals of equity crowd-funding – a relatively novel sector that is taking on the globe, and one that you will benefit from understanding.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_739" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/what-is-corporate-registry.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-739" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/what-is-corporate-registry-300x250.png" alt="what is corporate registry" width="300" height="250" /></a> what is corporate registry[/caption]\r\n\r\nIncorporation and corporate registries are just two of many concepts that you can benefit from finding out a bit more about, no matter who you are. If you’re a business, you can significantly decrease your liability for assorted business ventures by learning about incorporation and corporate registries. If you’re a non-profit, you may significantly appreciate the official recognition that joining a corporate registry provides. If you’re a sole proprietor, or a member of a partnership, you can register the name of your business, keeping it entirely your own. Corporate registries even benefit the general public – if you’re an everyday citizen, and are looking to purchase services or goods from any of the above-mentioned organizations, a corporate registry can provide you with much of the information you need to make educated commercial decisions.\r\n\r\n<em>So, first of all, what is incorporation, what is registration, and what is a corporate registry?</em>\r\n\r\nIncorporation is the process of forming a new corporation, in the legal sense: of creating an entity that is recognized as a distinct object under the law. Incorporation procedures vary from country to country, but the benefits of incorporating a business are generally the same: doing so protects you from personal harm, should lawsuits emerge against your business; it allows you to transfer ownership of your corporation to others; it contributes to the establishment of retirement funds; it often allows you to be taxed at a lower rate than an individual; finally, it has benefits where investors, durability, and organizational credit scores are concerned.\r\n\r\nIncorporation creates a separate legal entity: a business. This has all of the aforementioned benefits. However, when you’re done <em>creating </em>a business and actually want to <em>conduct </em>business, you may be required by regional law, depending upon the nature of your work, to obtain a business license in order to operate: to do this, you need to register your business. Note that not all registered businesses <em>have</em> to be incorporated – that’s a personal-professional decision. However, most incorporated businesses must register in order to be able to run.\r\n\r\nRegistration differs from region to region. Typically, however, it involves searching for and reserving a name, determining and inputting details (<em>e.g.</em>, your business’s location, whether or not you want employees and subcontractors, your anticipated monthly sales), and paying a fee. This process must be carried out every few years to ensure that your registration is up-to-date.\r\n\r\nA corporate registry, as its name suggests, is just a centralized storage of information concerning registered corporations – organizations that have, in other words, been incorporated, and have paid a fee to be registered in a governmentally-certified list of businesses. Most corporate registries see companies through the entirety of their incorporated lives, filing documents concerning incorporation, registration, maintenance, and dissolution of businesses and non-profits. Corporate registries, varying provincially in the case of Canada, also serve to provide a legal framework within which the corporations in their jurisdiction should operate. Finally, corporate registries serve the secondary – but nevertheless vital – purpose of disseminating this information to the public – anyone on the Internet can search a corporate registry to retrieve information about, often, thousands of domestic corporations.\r\n\r\n<em>What are the benefits of registering a business?</em>\r\n\r\nRegistering a business with the state or local government is not required to actually carry out business transactions. If I want something, and you sell it to me, we’re covered where that’s concerned. So, why register, theoretically, in the first place?\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>You need to be registered, often, to open a business bank account! </strong>A business bank account is always good, as it’s just one way of segmenting your personal activities from your professional ones. It also looks better where clients are concerned, as the name being given to them is one affiliated with an organization, not just an individual.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>You need to prove that you’re actually a business to get loans – registration is one way to do that! </strong>In order for banks to loan you money, they need to be able to validate that you’re <em>actually</em> a business, and not just a particularly optimistic individual. Registration documentation helps show banks and other funding agencies that you’ve carried out procedures the state considers fitting, and that you’ll be responsible with their money.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>You need new customers to have assurance that you’re legitimate – <em>bam</em>, registration! </strong>While personal connections may trust that you’re worth the investment, people who don’t know you won’t. Registration, again, shows onlookers that you’re real, and builds trust with novel customer groups.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>You need official state or provincial paperwork to get access to the kinds of wholesale rates that suppliers reserve for “official” business owners! Same goes for government contracts! </strong>Suppliers preferentially allocate discounted rates to registered businesses; government contracts actually <em>require </em>you to be registered, often.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>You need registration to manage employee taxation!</strong> If you’re planning to hire full-time employees, you’re going to need to navigate state taxes on their behalves. As such, register for a comparatively smooth run when taxation comes into play.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>You can gain recognition from potential clients online! </strong>Registering a business often means that you become a part of a corporate registry – that you’re listed, in other words, and that all that positive information you’ve worked so hard to make a reality is readily accessible to potential customers.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnd most important you need to be incorporated as a business if you want to utilize Equity Crowdfunding.', 'The Fundamental Facts #1: What is a corporate registry?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'fundamental-facts-1-corporate-registry', '', '', '2015-06-09 15:56:54', '2015-06-09 15:56:54', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=675', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(676, 10, '2015-04-14 15:40:24', '2015-04-14 15:40:24', 'On May 5<sup>th</sup>, 2015, CrowdFundBeat Media will be holding the Canadian Equity CrowdFunding Symposium – an educational event geared at getting traditional, private investors and crowdfunders talking about their industry, learning from venture capital experts, and networking with one another.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/300by250ad-toronto-may5-201-3-250x200-1.png"><img class="alignleft wp-image-677 size-full" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/300by250ad-toronto-may5-201-3-250x200-1.png" alt="Crowdfunding Canada" width="250" height="200" /></a>\r\n\r\nHappening at The Spoke Club (600 King Street West) in Toronto on May 5<sup>th</sup>, this symposium promises to be an event to remember, and – more importantly – to get a lot of value out of! This event will introduce you to current fundraising and marketing strategies that incorporate crowdfunding, will teach you more about assorted crowdfunding platforms, and will give you the chance to interact with those working to make equity crowdfunding legal in Canada! Specific topics to be discussed include the past, present, and future of crowdfunding and securities, SME lending and investing real estate crowdfunding, perq-based versus equity crowdfunding, assorted accelerators, StartUp Canada, and market validation.\r\n\r\nCrowdfunding expert speakers who have confirmed their attendance include Brian Koscak (Chairman of the Private Capital Markets Association of Canada, Co-Founder of the Equity Crowdfunding Alliance of Canada, and a partner at Cassels Brock &amp; Blackwell LLP in corporate and securities law), Matthew McGrath (a senior partner at Optimize Wealth Management, and former Executive Council Vice President of RBC), Scott Dublin (Director of Investor Relations at OurCrowd, an online platform for investing in start-ups around the world), Sandi Gilbert (Founder and CEO of SeedUps Canada, another novel crowdfund investing platform), Sydney Armani (CrowdFundBeat.com’s own!), Gil Michel-Garcia (one of our own Interim General Counsel members, and Co-Founder and CEO of WAFU), Alixe Cormick (a securities attorney at Venture Law Corporation), Steven Cinelli (Founder of PRIMARQ), Rod Ponce (CIO of BHIVE Social Media Labs), Joseph Barisonzi (CEO of CommunityLeader), and, most recently, KoreConX’s own <a href="https://ca.linkedin.com/in/oscarjofre" target="_blank">Oscar Jofre</a>!\r\n\r\n<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/oscar.jpg"><img class="alignleft wp-image-570 size-full" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/oscar.jpg" alt="oscar" width="305" height="256" /></a>Born in Chile and passionate about both technology and entrepreneurship, Oscar has dealt in senior management, marketing, investor relations, and sales, among others; he is Founder and President/CEO of KoreConX, well-known in eco-system infrastructure platforms (ESIP) for capital markets and crowdfunding, and a member of the Crowdfunding Intermediary Regulatory Advocates in the USA, as well as the Founder of the Equity Crowdfunding Alliance of Canada. He has been granted numerous awards, being recognized as one of the ten most influential Hispanic leaders in Canada, as an accomplished man by Rt. Hon. Stephen Harper, and as Vision 2012 Business Man of the Year by the Toronto Hispanic Chamber of Commerce.\r\n\r\nIf you’re any of the following people, we believe you could potentially benefit from the Canadian Equity CrowdFunding Symposium:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Private investors (venture capitalists and business angels)! </strong>Numerous excellent opportunities to invest are likely to present themselves.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Start-ups and innovators! </strong>Learn about an emerging market that you can involve yourselves in, and one that’s currently taking the world by storm.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Crowdfunding platforms! </strong>One of the central objectives of the Canadian Equity CrowdFunding Symposium is to broadcast word of novel platforms, and highlight their benefits.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Marketing specialists, legal advisors, and CPAs! </strong>Several of our expert speakers have backgrounds in management, marketing, and the legal sphere; they may be able to explain equity crowdfunding and its benefits in a way that is relatable to your field.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Students! </strong>Yes – you can (and should) profit from finding out about equity crowdfunding before you enter the business world!</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Journalists and business bloggers! </strong>This kind of event, particularly in light of the people coming, will definitely make social media waves – ride along!</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Anyone interested!</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCumulatively, on May 5<sup>th</sup>, come out for a wonderful day filled with expert advice, networking opportunities, and future-forward information, featuring KoreConeX’s own <a title="Oscar A Jofre" href="https://ca.linkedin.com/in/oscarjofre" target="_blank">Oscar Jofre</a>!\r\n\r\n<strong>REGISTER TODAY and DONT MISS OUT</strong>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.crowdfundbeat.ca/canadian-crowdfunding-symposium-may-5-2015-toronto/" target="_blank">http://www.crowdfundbeat.ca/canadian-crowdfunding-symposium-may-5-2015-toronto/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Oscar Jofre is coming to the Canadian Equity CrowdFunding Symposium! Save the date: May 5th, 2015!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'oscar-jofre-is-coming-to-the-canadian-equity-crowdfunding-symposium-save-the-date-may-5th-2015', '', '', '2015-04-14 15:40:24', '2015-04-14 15:40:24', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=676', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(677, 4, '2015-04-14 14:56:38', '2015-04-14 14:56:38', '', 'Crowdfunding Canada', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', '300by250ad-toronto-may5-201-3-250x200-1', '', '', '2015-04-14 14:56:49', '2015-04-14 14:56:49', '', 676, 'http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/300by250ad-toronto-may5-201-3-250x200-1.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0);
