(691, 10, '2015-05-11 18:37:52', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Thus far, in our “Equity Crowdfunding Around the World” series, we’ve discussed recent equity\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_729" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Austraila.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-729" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Austraila-300x250.png" alt="Austrailan Equity Crowdfunding" width="300" height="250" /></a> Austrailan Equity Crowdfunding[/caption]\r\n\r\ncrowdfunding-related happenings in Canada, the USA, Mexico, and China. We haven’t, however, as yet figured out what’s going on Down Under; as such, for those of you to whom it’s relevant, let’s take a look at the state of crowdfunding in Australia, as well as some of Australia’s biggest, perpetually-growing platforms.\r\n\r\nCrowdfunding in Australia advanced significantly in December of 2014, when the Abbott government released a discussion paper concerning regulations that Australia could implement to protect investors, and thereby move crowdfunding a step closer to being a feasible, dependable reality. While crowdfunding has been slow to be definitively regulated everywhere (as we’ve mentioned, regulatory legislation is not as yet completely finalized anywhere, really – even in the USA and Canada), Australia has been particularly slow on the crowdfunding uptake. As such, many financial leaders in Australia were calling upon the government to investigate regulatory regimes for crowdfunding. Commonwealth Bank boss <a href="http://www.smh.com.au/business/crowdfunding-in-australia-a-step-closer-20141208-122nkv.html">David Murray</a>, in particular, inputted a lot of effort into leading an inquiry report that urged the government to take action. Murray, specifically, pointed out that Australia’s government could learn from New Zealand’s, which had revived legislation permitting crowdfunding to occur; he also noted that a well-developed crowdfunding system could significantly broaden “innovation and competition” in the Australian financial system, which is filled with start-ups that, like those in Mexico, face difficulty accessing capital. <a href="http://www.smh.com.au/business/crowdfunding-in-australia-a-step-closer-20141208-122nkv.html">Chris Gilbert</a>, Co-Founder of Equitise, concurred, noting that crowdfunding is “potentially a very powerful tool for early-stage, higher-risk ventures to raise capital in Australia”.\r\n\r\nWhile other business-savvy Australians were as just as enthusiastic as Murray when it came to engaging with equity crowdfunding, Scale Investors CEO <a href="http://www.smh.com.au/business/crowdfunding-in-australia-a-step-closer-20141208-122nkv.html">Laura McKenzie</a> – who openly supports crowdfunding – noted that it’s critical that the new tool be “enhanced with an education program both around the risks involved and the portfolio approach required”. As always, education is an important aspect of implementing crowdfunding in a meaningful and safe way.\r\n\r\nSince December, however, Australia has come a long way. In fact, as of April 24<sup>th</sup>, 2015, Ingogo – a taxi app – is hoping to use equity-based crowdfunding platform Venturecrowd to raise Australia’s largest equity crowdfunding round yet, raising up to $4 million. Ingogo Founder and CEO <a href="http://www.businessinsider.com.au/ingogo-is-hoping-to-pull-off-australias-largest-equity-crowdfunding-round-by-raising-up-to-4-million-2015-4">Hamish Petrie</a> pointed out that equity crowdfunding has unique advantages, in that it helped him “reach a range of investors we simply wouldn’t reach through traditional channels”.\r\n\r\nAt present, there are several Australian and New Zealand-based crowdfunding platforms, including:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Australian Small Scale Offerings Board (ASSOB)</a>: focuses on raising capital for unlisted companies</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">CleanteachFundr</a>: offering businesses the opportunities to connect donations ranging between $5 and $100 over a maximally ninety-day-period – this particular platform operates on an all-or-nothing model, meaning that if the campaign does not reach its goal in the time allotted, no money is actually donated</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Chuffed</a>: this platform is specifically geared at community organizations, not-for-profits, and social enterprises – the first in Australia to specifically raise funding from a third-party social innovation investor; Chuffed is also interesting in that it helps customers design their campaigns</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">GiggedIn</a>: a platform specifically focused on ticketing for live music events, this can be used by venues, musicians, and event planners to organize the aforementioned events</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">OzCrowd</a>: a platform open to a range of funding – personal, donations, social enterprises, business, projects, and otherwise</li>\r\n	<li>Other platforms include iPledg, Pozible, Publishizer, ReadyFundGo, Sportaroo, Sproutback, Stage Label, StartSomeGood, TeamBus, Thinkable, and Thunder Funds, all of which have slightly different focuses and methodologies</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCumulatively, then, while Australia is a bit behind where equity crowdfunding regulation is concerned, some platforms have, clearly, been advancing, and now is as good a team as any to get involved in Australian innovation! It should also be noted that significant equity crowdfunding milestones are being had in New Zealand, for those interested in learning more about Oceania as a whole.', 'Equity Crowdfunding Around the World: Australian Focus', '', 'pending', 'open', 'closed', '', 'equity-crowdfunding-around-world-australian-focus', '', '', '2015-05-11 18:37:52', '2015-05-11 18:37:52', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=691', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(692, 10, '2015-04-29 17:59:27', '2015-04-29 17:59:27', 'KoreConX’s “Equity Crowdfunding Around the World” series has thus far taken readers to Canada, the USA, Australia, Mexico, and China; examining all these countries, we noted that crowdfunding had taken off more or less everywhere, and that it really has become a global phenomenon. The last Spanish-speaking country we took a look at, in fact, had made tremendous strides were crowdfunding was concerned; it appears that Chile, too, has seen crowdfunding gain popularity!<del></del><a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Chile.png"><img class=" size-medium wp-image-731 alignright" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Chile-300x250.png" alt="Chile" width="300" height="250" /></a>\r\n\r\nSpecifically, <a href="http://santiagotimes.cl/crowdfunding-takes-chile-energizes-entrepreneurship-region/">Daleimpulso</a>, founded in May 2014, grants Chileans the opportunity to raise capital via crowdfunding for certain products; entrepreneurs cite crowdfunding as “a huge opportunity” to take their projects forward, to test products and see who buys them, and to collect information they otherwise would not be able to access.\r\n\r\nThe Chilean economy as a whole appears to mirror this sentiment: one largely reliant on the mining industry, the country’s economy is now striving to push for innovation and entrepreneurship in the business sector; this appears to be working, as Chile is now ranked <a href="http://santiagotimes.cl/crowdfunding-takes-chile-energizes-entrepreneurship-region/">fifth</a> in entrepreneurial activity in the world, and it is estimated that <a href="http://santiagotimes.cl/crowdfunding-takes-chile-energizes-entrepreneurship-region/">six firms</a> are created each year in Chile for every one thousand working-age individuals.\r\n\r\nThe capital, specifically, is a great place for crowdfunding, according to <a href="http://www.crowdsourcing.org/editorial/first-equity-crowdfunding-project-in-chile-raises-135000/27057">Jose Bernos</a>, Broota Co-Founder and CTO. He notes that Chile is very centralized – that many young people migrate from all regions of Chile to its capital because of the capital’s excellent educational and professional resources; they stay there during university and beyond. To put things into perspective, of the country’s seventeen million people, eight million live in the capital. As such, crowdfunding is a good way for other regions to prosper – someone living down south, for example, can upload a project, and the northern hub can contribute to funding it, as well.\r\n\r\nOne particularly successful instance of crowdfunding, in fact, took place in Chile as early as 2013: an equity-based platform called Broota, located in Santiago, helped a north-Chilean brewery called the <a href="http://www.crowdsourcing.org/editorial/first-equity-crowdfunding-project-in-chile-raises-135000/27057">Cerveza Guayacan brewery</a> raise approximately $135 000. Forty-eight investors participated, and the funding round lasted forty-three days, with investments ranging from $60 to $20 000.\r\n\r\nWhile crowdfunding is, then, set to prosper in Chile, there are, as always, obstacles to its being implemented and embraced nation-wide. Some entrepreneurs, for example, point out the fact that “Chileans are <a href="http://santiagotimes.cl/crowdfunding-takes-chile-energizes-entrepreneurship-region/">not used</a> to purchasing goods online”; without proper education to accompany equity crowdfunding, everyday Chileans may not be as eager to get involved in supporting entrepreneurs via the Web.\r\n\r\nThere is also the fact that successes like the one spoken above aren’t exactly occurring at a standardly “commercial” level. Specifically, of those investing in Cerveza Guayacan, approximately ninety-five percent were friends and family, friends of friends, or very good brewery clients. Jose Bernos hopes that people will eventually start seeing crowdfunding “in a more rational way, and will see it as a way to invest in venture capital”, but acknowledges that, at the moment, he is “not expecting that, only emotional investments”. This brings to mind another problem: the regulations and rules that usually accompany nation-wide implementation of crowdfunding. We’ve seen just how problematic it is to standardize crowdfunding legislation, even in locales where the practice is popular (<em>e.g.</em>, Canada, the USA). As such, it could be some years before Chile has a legally well-established, popular crowdfunding market.\r\n\r\nThis, however, has not stopped Chile from amassing <a href="http://www.universocrowdfunding.com/plataformas-de-crowdfunding-en-latinoamerica/">several crowdfunding platforms</a>. To get some perspective on the platforms available in Chile and the remainder of Latin America, take a look below:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Broota: described as one of the first platforms of equity crowdfunding in Latin America, Broota has successfully orchestrated several campaigns, including the one described above</li>\r\n	<li>me: geared exclusively at supporting social projects; focused on Chile, Mexico, and Brazil</li>\r\n	<li>me: a site catering to creators, artists, and founders of start-ups; originating in Chile, it has expanded to Argentina, Brazil, Mexico, Uruguay, and the USA</li>\r\n	<li>Suelten las lucas: a platform singularly dedicated to cultural and artistic initiatives and their funding</li>\r\n	<li>com: related mostly to clean-energy crowdfunding</li>\r\n	<li>it: primarily geared at urban architecture projects</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCumulatively, then, while crowdfunding is still a novel concept in Chile, it has seen tremendous reception, and is a way for the country to further bolster its already-thriving entrepreneurial spirit! If you’re in Chile, or in Latin America in general, expect crowdfunding to keep building a solid base in the years to come!', 'Equity Crowdfunding Around the World: Chilean Focus', '', 'pending', 'open', 'closed', '', 'chilean-equity-crowdfunding', '', '', '2015-05-11 18:48:57', '2015-05-11 18:48:57', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=692', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(693, 10, '2015-05-11 18:55:54', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Continuing on with our “Equity Crowdfunding Around the World” series, let’s take a look at the United Kingdom: a region which has been likened to the USA in its capacity for crowdfunding. The UK has seen crowdfunding take off to significant extents in the last few years; as such, in this article, we will dominantly explore the best crowdfunding sites currently available to UK investors and entrepreneurs, groups that crowdfunding enthusiasts can involve themselves with in the region, as well as some recent UK developments where crowdfunding is concerned.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_737" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/UK.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-737" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/UK-300x250.png" alt="UK equity crowdfunding" width="300" height="250" /></a> UK equity crowdfunding[/caption]\r\n\r\nTo begin, as noted above, the crowdfunding craze is on in the UK. <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/investing/10435276/Which-are-the-best-crowdfunding-websites.html">Nicole Horlick</a>, for example – a fund manager in the UK – raised about £150,000 in 2013 in solely twenty-two hours, and she did it via crowdfunding; as a result, she was inspired to launch Money&amp;Co, her own crowdfunding website. She says that it’s a “no-brainer” crowdfunding has become so mainstream: after all, it “cuts out the middle man… allowing small businesses to get the funding they need without banks taking a slice of their margins in fees from when firms take our business loans”. In her mind, crowdfunding is also beneficial for investors: “these ventures offer the potential for much greater returns”. Finally, of course, crowdfunding websites themselves – which sometimes take a small percentage of money raised, or a piece of the returns paid to investors – also make some money. As such, from essentially everyone’s standpoint, crowdfunding is worth approaching.\r\n\r\nWhile crowdfunding may, then, seem to be something that one should get involved in as fast as possible, acquiring a solid crowdfunding education is necessary prior to taking the plunge. One group to be aware of is the UK Crowdfunding Association (<a href="http://www.ukcfa.org.uk/">UKCFA</a>), an organization that was formed in 2012 by fourteen crowdfunding businesses. The UKCFA aims to, among other things, promote crowdfunding as a way for ventures to raise funds, be the voice of crowdfunding businesses in the UK to the public, press, and policymakers, and publish a code of practice that will be adopted by UK crowdfunding businesses. In other words, the UKCFA is a great way to get involved in crowdfunding in the region, and to discover what’s currently occurring in the UK equity crowdfunding sphere. It’s also a good place to go if you’re interested in starting out in this space, but are not as yet certain how to proceed.\r\n\r\nFor those of us already participating in UK crowdfunding, it’s always useful to be aware of all the new and established platforms available to us! Some of the best crowdfunding websites in the UK, according to <em>The Telegraph</em>’s <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/investing/10435276/Which-are-the-best-crowdfunding-websites.html">Kyle Caldwell</a>, include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="Crowdcube.com">Crowdcube.com</a>: one of the longest-established sites, catering to a variety of firms who need to raise capital; many of these businesses are existing businesses seeking to gain more funding, and all of them are required to present responsibly-made financial projections to Crowdcube for approval</li>\r\n	<li><a href="Seedrs.com">Seedrs.com</a>: another well-established site, primarily geared at helping entrepreneurs get their first seed capital; investors can collect equity by providing capital</li>\r\n	<li><a href="SyndicateRoom.com">SyndicateRoom.com</a>: a comparatively new portal with a new concept, SyndicateRoom has small investors build on substantial stakes in a business that have already been bought by more established lead investors, which means that businesses need to procure funding from angels prior to being listed, which in turn makes them more prone to eventually reaching their fundraising goals</li>\r\n	<li><a href="InvestingZone.com">InvestingZone.com</a>: an even newer site, this one focuses on very early-stage companies</li>\r\n	<li><a href="Crowdfunder.co.uk%20i">Crowdfunder.co.uk i</a>s yet another platform worthy of consideration, as the UK’s largest crowdfunding network – it has launched thousands of projects and raised over £4M; it’s a sister site with Crowdcube, in fact</li>\r\n	<li>Wefund, another large crowdfunding platform – the largest, according to its website; it claims to be “the first to bring crowdfunding to the UK”</li>\r\n	<li>Countless other sites exist, including Unbound, MoolaHoop, Abundance Generation, and Trillion Fund</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCumulatively, a futuristic note: the UK’s rapid growth in the crowdfunding industry seems to show “no sign of abating”, with P2P lending being a large growth sector, followed by consumer lending. The UK’s government also seeks to be in support of crowdfunding, which adds to the industry’s promise. With the USA and other countries are bogged down with regulations, many crowdfunders in the UK believe that the European Commission’s interest and the support of the UK Financial Services Commissioner put the UK on track to, effectively, take over the crowdfunding world. If you’re doing work here, at the moment, you’re in luck!', 'Equity Crowdfunding Around the World: UK Focus', '', 'pending', 'open', 'closed', '', 'equity-crowdfunding-around-world-uk-focus', '', '', '2015-05-11 18:55:54', '2015-05-11 18:55:54', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=693', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(695, 10, '2015-05-11 18:46:58', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We have already examined equity crowdfunding in the context of Latin America before: specifically, we featured Chile in one of our prior “Equity Crowdfunding Around the World” pieces. Now, let’s take a look at Brazil: another Latin American nation that seems to have experienced a crowdfunding boom.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_730" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Brazil.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-730" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Brazil-300x250.png" alt="Brazil Equity Crowdfunding" width="300" height="250" /></a> Brazil Equity Crowdfunding[/caption]\r\n\r\nAccording to most sources, Brazil’s crowdfunding ecosystem is already “healthy and growing”. Specifically, the World Bank has noted that Brazil has over seventeen large crowdfunding sites, including Catarse – a site that calls itself “the biggest crowdfunding community in Brazil”, and that has helped over one thousand projects raise over $4.1 million in total. The practice first arrived in Brazil in 2009 through a site called Vakinha, which helped people fund businesses, projects, and personal matters (<em>e.g.</em>, plastic surgeries, new cars).\r\n\r\nThe legal status of crowdfunding in Brazil, presumably, remained unclear until about 2012, but in that year, Brazilian governing bodies still said that <a href="https://www.virtualwallstreet.com/crowdfund-brazil.shtml">no restrictions</a> existed on what could be done within the nation. Even in 2012, Brazil had about twenty to thirty crowdfunding sites: a good start, and one comparable to that of other countries! However, since, Brazil’s crowdfunding system has faced some obstacles: namely, the fact that doing business in Brazil often comes with the custo Brasil (the Brazil Cost): in other words, with countless bureaucratic and legal complications. Entrepreneurs unfamiliar with Brazilian restrictions may have a hard time making crowdfunding ends meet in the region, and Brazil won’t be of much help, given that it lacks the legal framework and proper e-commerce environment to successfully implement crowdfunding on a nation scale.\r\n\r\nMany Brazilians also feel that Brazil has <a href="http://www.crowdvalley.com/news/brazilian-crowdfunding-post-world-cup">not as yet</a> exploited the whole of its equity crowdfunding potential – a potential that exists at both the domestic and the international levels. While, as described, there is a great domestic interest in crowdfunding, Brazilian culture, arts, and projects are also valued internationally. Assuming that Brazil plays its cards right, crowdfunding could be utilized to attract international investors to Brazilian projects, thus further bolstering the economy. Brazil could also work with the remainder of South America, integrating in a Latin American platform that would bring in yet more investors, and service yet more entrepreneurs.\r\n\r\nConversely, many European and American platforms have recognized that Latin America – and Brazil in particular – is a compelling region to do crowdfunding with. These platforms have begun translating their websites in order to attract Brazilian investors; crowdfunding journalist Janet Gunter believes this is the result of companies’ recognition of the interest shown in crowdfunding by the Brazilian government.\r\n\r\nBrazilian platforms, conversely, have not dominantly been translated into English, or into any other language. This, actually, appears to be true for the entirety of Latin America: platforms and crowdfunding information sources are dominantly in Spanish or Portuguese, but do not appear in English translations. This is problematic, because it prevents Brazil and other Latin American countries from communicating with such crowdfunding hubs as Canada, the USA, and the UK. These Brazilian platforms also often lack international payment methods; this is non-ideal because many international investors are, as mentioned, interested in what Brazil has to offer; if they cannot contribute to Brazilian campaigns, Brazilian entrepreneurs have less potential capital at their disposal.\r\n\r\nNevertheless, <a href="http://thebrazilbusiness.com/article/brazilian-crowdfunding">many platforms</a> are up and about within Brazil itself, which creates ample opportunity for the Brazilian community. Demohour (which we have already examined in other Latin American countries) and Catarse are relatively successful, which means that Brazil is a <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/hsbc/2014/07/09/will-the-world-cup-spark-or-stifle-brazils-growth/">promising</a> emerging market for crowdfunding! Movere is another main crowdfunding website in Brazil! Some other platforms include Benfeitoria (a site focused on projects in accessibility, culture, education, music, and fashion) and Queremos (a platform that deals with financing foreign events (<em>e.g.</em>, concerts)).', 'Equity Crowdfunding Around the World: Brazil in Focus', '', 'pending', 'open', 'closed', '', 'equity-crowdfunding-brazil-in-focus', '', '', '2015-05-11 18:46:58', '2015-05-11 18:46:58', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=695', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(696, 10, '2015-05-11 18:53:21', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Thus far, in our “Equity Crowdfunding Around the World” series, we’ve examined North America, Latin America, parts of Asia, and parts of Europe in trying to gauge the scope of equity crowdfunding on a global level. Now, let’s take a look at another country in Europe, and see how equity crowdfunding is performing within it. The focus of this article is Italy, a region in which equity crowdfunding, it would seem, is again experiencing a considerable boom!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_733" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Italian.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-733" src="http://koreconx.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Italian-300x250.png" alt="Italian Equity Crowdfunding" width="300" height="250" /></a> Italian Equity Crowdfunding[/caption]\r\n\r\nAs early as <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2014/08/48023-equity-crowdfunding-italy-today/">2012</a>, the Italian parliament issued a law on startups that made equity crowdfunding possible. Within one year of publication of these regulations, nine portals had been authorized in Italy; by 2014, each of the first three had raised capital of over one million Euros.\r\n\r\nWhile things look like they’re off to a relatively good start for Italy, then, it should be noted that problems still exist for Italy where crowdfunding is concerned. The <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2014/08/48023-equity-crowdfunding-italy-today/">first challenge</a> is, as always, regulation – there are relatively strong limitations introduced by legislation and the CONSOB regulation. Specifically, only some companies were, until recently, allowed to raise risk capital online – namely, “innovative start-ups” – which limits crowdfunding to high-risk enterprises; while this has now been changed, the equity crowdfunding space is still restricted. The <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2014/08/48023-equity-crowdfunding-italy-today/">second challenge</a> is that the Italian market has a propensity for risk, and it may therefore be difficult to reach the size necessary to sustain a few equity crowdfunding platforms concurrently.\r\n\r\nInnovation is nevertheless continually being had in Italy: 2015 will see the Global Entrepreneurship Congress and EXPO in Milan, making this an important year for Italian crowdfunding history. Italy was also the <a href="http://www.telecomitalia.com/tit/en/ambiente-sociale/cos-e-il-crowdfunding.html">first</a> country in Europe to have a law that regulates equity crowdfunding, predominantly because of the economic crisis that struck Italy in 2008, and resulted in a decree created to stimulate economic growth in the country. Equity crowdfunding is seen by this bill as a tool that can greatly ameliorate Italy’s concentration of innovative start-ups through exploiting the Web.\r\n\r\nAs of 2015, Italy also expanded equity crowdfunding to include “<a href="http://www.growvc.com/blog/2015/01/italy-expands-equity-crowdfunding-to-innovative-smes/">innovative SMEs</a>” – firms with a more than €50 million annual turnover, and that meet at least one of the following three requirements: 3% of either sales or costs are attributable to R&amp;D activities, one third of employees have a degree or one fifth of employees are doing or have done a doctorate program, and the company owns a patent. This means that equity crowdfunding now has a bigger user base in the country, which, in turn, translates to more opportunities for investors to pitch in to!\r\n\r\nCumulatively, then, it’s clear that equity crowdfunding is up and running in Italy: while its regulations were a tad restrictive from the get-go, Italy was the first country to adapt to equity crowdfunding, and to consider it meaningful enough to craft a related regulatory regime. Now, several equity crowdfunding portals exist in Italy, so opportunities for the investor working with either innovative start-ups or innovate SMEs have dramatically increased. While we are certain that many other portals exist, here are some that have previously been featured on <a href="http://www.crowdclan.com/equity-crowdfunding-portals-in-italy/">Crowdclan.com</a>:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Derev: first created in 2012, and now an international network for universities, corporations, and other institutions with an interest in arts, culture, technology, politics, and activism</li>\r\n	<li>SiamoSoci: its primary objective is to accelerate the process of growing startups; it occupies about 3.7% of the national seed and venture capital market – a large portal, in other words</li>\r\n	<li>StarsUp: the first CONSOB-authorized portal, this one seeks to pair good ideas with valuable consultants</li>\r\n	<li>Unicaseed: a brokerage company offering trading and investment counselling in conjunction with crowdfunding</li>\r\n	<li>WeAreStarting: a 2013 portal geared at increasing early entrepreneurs’ visibility</li>\r\n	<li>Two other portals include Assiteca Crowd and CrowdfundMe, respectively one of the first equity crowdfunding portals in Italy, and one of the newest portals around</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Equity Crowdfunding Around the World: Italian Focus', '', 'pending', 'open', 'closed', '', 'equity-crowdfunding-around-world-italian-focus', '', '', '2015-05-11 18:53:21', '2015-05-11 18:53:21', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=696', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(697, 10, '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We at KoreConX really believe that equity crowdfunding is the way to go. Investors! You are living in an exciting era, one that promises you an abundance of opportunities and also the chance to get to know about those opportunities in a very agile and efficient manner. What makes the process of investing even more exciting now is the presence of an entirely new ecosystem that is characterized by several hundreds of equity portals that facilitate all stakeholders who are part of an investment. At KoreConX, we have also launched an equity portal system which not only supports crowdfunding platforms, but also looks after capital markets for you. We believe that with the help of our equity portal, called the eco-system infrastructure platform (ESIP), you will be facilitated throughout your investment during different its phases, such as pre-during-post crowdfunding transactions. Our equity portal will help you by maintaining due diligence of issuers, data repository, or deal room, and will also help in shareholder management and communications, something that is quite revolutionary in today’s modern world of transparency. Finally, for every type of investor, whether you are a CEO, a lawyer, auditor, or even a third-party provider, we have provided a safe and secure platform with a single point of entry to prevent leakage and mishandling of corporate or personal information.\r\n\r\nToday, due to cloud computing, elegant software solutions, efficient distribution channels, learning about validation and testing techniques, globalized sharing of information, social media, and online marketing, the world of business and commerce holds more potential than ever. You have been given the opportunity to not only know about businesses in a more transparent manner, but also to invest in them via modern investment opportunities like equity crowdfunding. Equity crowdfunding, as opposed to crowdfunding alone, is a more recent global phenomenon which has opened an entirely new world for investors of any kind. While crowdfunding alone only lead to recognition for financial support in the success of the company, equity crowdfunding now allows investors to have a stake in a company which is still in its infancy stages. Due to the nature of this investment opportunity, the business landscape has been reformed, and continues to be so in significant ways. While the traditional business landscape favored large investments typically facilitated by venture capital firms to companies which were far advanced in terms of their development, the new business landscape is being quickly filled up with small businesses early on in their development – start-ups, in other words – which have a tremendous advantage in terms of potential, but also come with a larger risk from an investor’s point of view. However, if treaded carefully, the investor can make shrewd decisions about equity crowdfunding, just like any other investment.\r\n\r\nIf you are an American investor today, enjoying the entrepreneurship boom and concurrent rise in hundreds of equity crowdfunding portals, you have, as discussed above, many, many opportunities. Not only is this phenomenon reaching epic proportions – it is also very recent: the US only legalized the equity crowdfunding landscape last year (March 2014); since legalization, the US equity crowdfunding landscape has seen the inception of over 1000 websites dedicated to this phenomenon. Equity crowdfunding is expected to grow even more this year, for up to $17 billion after having been forecasted for $10 billion in 2014. The sheer number of platforms dedicated to this phenomenon is very good news for any American investor. Anybody today can contribute to a concept that they feel related to or interested in, and can become part of the company’s journey. While the majority of these platforms require that you be an accredited investor, you still have options with other platforms which do not require that on an absolute basis.\r\n\r\nHere, then, is a short list of equity crowdfunding platforms in the US via which you can invest:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fangel.co%2F&amp;ei=XSE9VYi2E7DdsATbzoH4DA&amp;usg=AFQjCNG07Amw4_R3yedobbYoJNxKqpcaGw&amp;sig2=cC0NpjUFEnMwX0waGxmWYQ&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">AngelList</a>: This only accepts accredited investors</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fcircleup.com%2F&amp;ei=gyE9VZTyG4rmsATYmICwDQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNG0joLuK4FU07n2-SDf0ijhiWXLoQ&amp;sig2=5j8ImQ6x6ZLltmPGjeKzrw&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">CircleUp</a>: This only accepts accredited investors</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCAQFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.earlyshares.com%2F&amp;ei=kiE9VcifHuLLsAT034CYBw&amp;usg=AFQjCNG9lZBbjRxNnHF4TNrYWLZak-Tu8w&amp;sig2=xeSMCx3V1WSYf2pQri_r_Q&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Early Shares</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCkQFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.equitynet.com%2F&amp;ei=niE9VaWDPLHmsATT8oCQAg&amp;usg=AFQjCNEQwPyzqFmqiQjfUoI-Li8m2HE38w&amp;sig2=rq1OWfbucEduHKIsvS-Whg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">EquityNet</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.fundable.com%2F&amp;ei=rCE9VY3MFfOIsQS4wYDwDA&amp;usg=AFQjCNH7YfJxcp-qeioDqEce0_15nTNh-Q&amp;sig2=X2bp_QRbVPK1lqTpqUD86g&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Fundable</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Ffundersclub.com%2F&amp;ei=tyE9VZrNK-ewsASfzYDQCQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNHsWRJpSA4lqciMkg0BOU2Kl6qIPQ&amp;sig2=LPh0QYJqFzB2datCYX6L8w&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">FundersClub</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;sqi=2&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gofundme.com%2F&amp;ei=wiE9Vbe1GZTasASYw4C4Cg&amp;usg=AFQjCNF2Y3v9Xh3dW90mqt_jWXSkhoq_QA&amp;sig2=pfdbbzcYa9_yBSDKg0P32Q&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">GoFundMe</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=2&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCgQFjAB&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.investedin.com%2F&amp;ei=zSE9VcHHEJLIsQSooIDoAQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNFBUdGjSv4ss0mmmTHp5wZ_wOd-KQ&amp;sig2=LtUebXaD_add4Uj2Vle9Jg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Investedin</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CC8QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.lendingclub.com%2F&amp;ei=4iE9VbuROaTHsQSg2oDACw&amp;usg=AFQjCNGJab0rLwlxcqtrgGNcYykayTDyhw&amp;sig2=nwIb-60V7G-b8mHY3HvqaA&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Lending Club</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCkQFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fmicroventures.com%2F&amp;ei=8CE9Vai7B6HLsAS2poDwCw&amp;usg=AFQjCNFoXSiyIkVOLmJ2ZmTuprDuOog1tw&amp;sig2=RdkJxNIAUTZfgQSUgboNPg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">MicroVentures</a>: This only accepts accredited investors</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.seedinvest.com%2F&amp;ei=AyI9VYW5K4LfsASvtIHACw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEz3pNHfsDEPVGWp7cIajG-1zI5tQ&amp;sig2=j8PGtP9E-CsWnoeMgP50qw&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">SeedInvest</a>: This only accepts accredited investors</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CB0QFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.startupvalley.com%2F&amp;ei=EiI9VZLjMbK1sATVkYGIDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNG-5HYBQswdb18FlLNsnoTKzcP9Ew&amp;sig2=mN5vurb-OfsnfkI1tS5WMw&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">StartupValley</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=2&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CCgQFjAB&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.upstart.com%2F&amp;ei=ISI9VZKFBLiIsQT1woCYDg&amp;usg=AFQjCNGMBG61yDpywtbRhX3Z_R6lOw05Rw&amp;sig2=MMPicrU05BzNLx-tCpvwVg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Upstart</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=4&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;sqi=2&amp;ved=0CDcQFjAD&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.crunchbase.com%2Forganization%2Frock-the-post&amp;ei=NSI9VcSHFYLisATHqYCABA&amp;usg=AFQjCNF0BBqCyAROw0BhNSXatjhikY_nKA&amp;sig2=frsQhXVnA5r3LQxXSdRZaA&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">RockThePost</a>: Open to all</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCumulatively, as an American investor, you have over fourteen premier portals to choose from; many more are just a click away, if you are interested in something more specific!', 'Common Questions: I am an American investor, where can I invest?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', 'common-questions-american-investor-can-invest', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=697', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(698, 10, '2015-04-29 17:53:40', '2015-04-29 17:53:40', 'We at KoreConX believe that equity crowdfunding has become a game changer for all parties involved in an investment. Investors are no longer recognized just for their timely and essential help to the company – they can also reap profits by having a stake in the company. The presence of a virtually unlimited amount of equity crowdfunding websites and platforms has facilitated the origin of a brand new ecosystem which protects all parties involved in the process, and also provides an abundance of opportunities for different types of entrepreneurs to seek help from a variety of investors.\r\n\r\nWhile anybody can benefit from investing via an equity crowdfunding portal, from an entrepreneurs’ point of view, it is important that equity crowdfunding is seen to pave a way for a successful partnership. The term “partnership” is very important, because it emphasizes the inherent collaboration the entrepreneur needs to have with the investor. The entrepreneur may have invested all his time and financial resources, and even sacrificed his previous job to start this venture, but there may come a time when the entrepreneur seeks funds to further his venture, needs technical or strategic guidance to solve bigger or deep-rooted problems associated with his business, capital is stuck in overproduction of inventory, equipment is not commercialized (leading to inefficiency in production), or there is a problem with the business concept. In all of these situations, the entrepreneur dearly needs help from the outside to prevent his “baby” from failing. The last thing that an entrepreneur could think of would be to lose everything he has worked so hard for, and therefore, an equity crowdfunding deal can be advantageous to this entrepreneur, provided that it is sought for the right reasons and the partnership has resulted in the right fit between what the investor can bring to the table and what the entrepreneur needs in return.\r\n\r\nBased on the needs of an entrepreneur and the value that the investor brings, the equity of the company given to the investor can be decided. This too is risky for the entrepreneur, as giving too much equity could easily allow the investor to take control of the business, and similarly giving too little equity may drive the investor away, because they feel that they don’t have significant returns on their investment. In order to prepare for this, it is always a good idea to seek a valuation of the company from independent advisors. Based on this, the entrepreneur may give an appropriate amount of his company in return for the services he seeks.\r\n\r\nSometimes, however, a partnership does not result in a desirable position. This may happen either with one or many investors, but in the latter case, the position might become too complicated for an entrepreneur to deal with. Many investors, each of whom have their own vision of the company and their opinions about how to solve problems, might become challenging for the entrepreneur. In this case, the entrepreneur goes from focussing on the company to focussing on mediating the investors. He has to apply extra energy to make sure there is no confusion rather than applying this extra energy to removing the problem itself. The advantage that the entrepreneur has here is that he is still in control of his business, and he can take more investors in or buy back in the company and return the number of investors to one at which he feels comfortable.\r\n\r\nIn today’s business landscape, in which there are unlimited avenues via which to start a business, faster distribution channels, greater efficiency in production, reduced costs of maintaining a small scale business (from 150K in 2000 to 1500 in 2010 for a software company), greater commercialization, increased information sharing, and an attitude towards innovation and working for yourself to make it big rather than working a 9 to 5 job, equity crowdfunding is a dream come true for the entrepreneur. Anybody now holds the potential to start with literally nothing except an idea that meets a special market demand, and some capital from outside to become a millionaire if the business plan is executed properly. Equity crowdfunding has played a pivotal role in transforming average citizens into company CEOs. Apart from just financial and strategic guidance that the investment allows, equity crowdfunding also provides more subtle but equally powerful benefits. Some of these benefits include reducing risk, testing the market via pre-sell, validation of a concept, and finally, free PR. Once the idea or the concept is put to the test by bringing it to an equity crowdfunding platform, the entrepreneur not only seeks an investment, but he also sees the validity of his idea when other people come on board and believe in the idea in the same way he does. Putting the idea out there also means free marketing, and if the idea is very powerful and transformative, our digital and online social media ensures that the word gets spread fast. Within minutes, an entrepreneur can be connected to powerful investors, who may change the world of the company in a positive way with a phone call, or key pieces of insight that the entrepreneur was missing.', 'Advantages of equity crowdfunding: entrepreneurs’ point of view', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', 'advantages-of-equity-crowdfunding-entrepreneurs-point-of-view', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '2015-05-11 07:26:48', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=698', 0, 'post', '', 0),
