(720, 10, '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In a past series, we examined equity crowdfunding in several global locales – specifically, we looked into crowdfunding ecosystems across Canada, the USA, Mexico, China, Australia, Chile, Brazil, the UK, and Italy: across, in other words, North America, Latin America, Asia, Oceania, and Europe. As is evident, then, equity crowdfunding is a truly global phenomenon, and the truth is that you can crowdfund nearly anywhere!\r\n\r\nTo put things into perspective, let’s take a look at some <a href="https://fundwisdom.com/article/fengjiayi/global-equity-crowdfunding-uk-us">World Bank data</a> from 2012, when crowdfunding had really just begun rearing its head in many countries. In that year alone, the following countries all had between one and three hundred crowdfunding investing platforms (CFIs): the USA, France, Italy, the UK, Spain, Netherlands, Germany, Brazil, Canada, Australia, South Africa, India, the Russian Federation, Belgium, Hong Kong, China, the UAE, and Estonia. Since, New Zealand, Sweden, and the East African country of Kenya have <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/wilschroter/2014/07/09/crowdfunding-around-the-world/2/">all engaged</a> in crowdfunding initiatives.\r\n\r\nIn sum, then, crowdfunding is essentially everywhere. But where <em>precisely</em> is “everywhere”? To quantify this generalization, here’s a list of places in the world where you can <em>definitely </em>do equity crowdfunding:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Canada: Canada is rife with crowdfunding and crowdfunding education, with events like the <a href="http://ncfacanada.org/2015-canadian-crowdfunding-summit-early-bird-registration-now-open/">Canadian Crowdfunding Summit</a> occurring for the first time in 2015, and organizations like the National Crowdfunding Association of Canada (<a href="http://ncfacanada.org/2015-canadian-crowdfunding-summit-early-bird-registration-now-open/">NCFA</a>) spear-heading the equity crowdfunding movement; over <a href="https://fundwisdom.com/article/fengjiayi/global-equity-crowdfunding-uk-us">thirty-four</a> Canadian equity crowdfunding platforms exist, as of 2012!</li>\r\n	<li>The USA: The USA is perhaps the most active country in the world where equity crowdfunding is concerned – close to 1000 equity crowdfunding sites exist in the USA as of March 2014! Further, equity crowdfunding is expected to grow in the USA in 2015 – the market may well hit <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jorge-newbery/crowdfunding-is-growing-u_b_4980206.html">$17 billion</a> this year</li>\r\n	<li>France: France has many, many crowdfunding platforms on <em>The Soho Loft’s </em><a href="http://thesoholoft.com/global-list-of-crowdfunding-sites/">list</a> of global crowdfunding sites; they span personal, creative, entrepreneurial, and social projects, as well as sites that specifically support students, musicians, sports, journalism, books, fashion, film, and more</li>\r\n	<li>Italy: Italy embraced crowdfunding as early as 2012; as of 2015, Italy has expanded its equity crowdfunding regulations to <a href="http://www.growvc.com/blog/2015/01/italy-expands-equity-crowdfunding-to-innovative-smes/">include</a> innovative small and medium businesses in crowdfunding activities; many crowdfunding portals exist in the country, as listed on <a href="http://www.crowdclan.com/equity-crowdfunding-portals-in-italy/">com</a></li>\r\n	<li>The UK: The UK is another crowdfunding hub, like the USA and Canada; <em>The Telegraph</em>’s Kyle Caldwell has compiled a <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/investing/10435276/Which-are-the-best-crowdfunding-websites.html">list</a> of some of the best crowdfunding websites in the region</li>\r\n	<li>Spain: Spain has <a href="http://thesoholoft.com/global-list-of-crowdfunding-sites/">several</a> crowdfunding platforms, including Verkami.com, Lanzanos.com, Injoinet.com, Goteo.org, and Fandyu.com</li>\r\n	<li>The Netherlands: Local crowdfunding platforms <a href="http://thesoholoft.com/global-list-of-crowdfunding-sites/">include</a>nl, 4just1.com, Greenwish.nl, Sellaband.com, Africaunsigned.com, Talentboek.nl, and Nieuwspost.nl</li>\r\n	<li>Brazil: Even in 2012, Brazil had about twenty to thirty crowdfunding sites; while many Brazilians feel that equity crowdfunding is yet to hit its potential in the country, <a href="http://thebrazilbusiness.com/article/brazilian-crowdfunding">many platforms</a> already exist within the country, creating ample opportunity for investors and entrepreneurs; these include Demohour and Catarse, both of which are considerably successful</li>\r\n	<li>Australia: Crowdfunding is most definitely not prohibited in Australia, though Australian crowdfunding regulation is a bit behind other places; several noteworthy platforms exist, including <a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Chuffed</a>, <a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">GiggedIn</a>, <a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">OzCrowd</a>, <a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">Cleantechfundr</a>, and the Australian Small Scale Offerings Board (<a href="https://www.google.ca/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=10&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0CFMQFjAJ&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.crowdfundit.com.au%2F2012%2F12%2F18%2Fcrowdfunding-platforms-in-australian-and-new-zealand%2F&amp;ei=HBg8VeTmHoaxsASji4HYDw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEKALc85gQFz0mEdIbaRwYZsVJUcw&amp;sig2=vX7yCuTGzL-b9An1keq9Gg&amp;bvm=bv.91665533,d.cWc">ASSOB</a>)</li>\r\n	<li>China: <em>Forbes</em>’s <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2014/07/17/china-has-a-chance-to-introduce-equity-crowdfunding-ahead-of-the-us-and-europe/">Conor Roche</a> believes China could “kick off a new wave in equity crowdfunding that might even leave the European and US-based philanthropic and rewards-based crowdfunding movements in the dust”! Specifically, on the basis of a look at China’s economic ecosystem, the World Bank has presumably suggested that Chinese crowdfunding could become a <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/berlinschoolofcreativeleadership/2014/07/17/china-has-a-chance-to-introduce-equity-crowdfunding-ahead-of-the-us-and-europe/2/">$50 billion</a> industry by just 2025</li>\r\n	<li>Mexico: Mexico is actually a relatively reasonable candidate for an equity crowdfunding boom, what with its “bustling engineering and innovation community”, as <em>Forbes’s</em> <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2013/05/14/is-equity-crowdfunding-coming-to-mexico/">Chance Barnett</a> describes it, and an ecosystem “ripe for entrepreneurial growth”; Crowdfunder has entered Mexico with <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2013/05/14/is-equity-crowdfunding-coming-to-mexico/">mx</a>, and several leading platforms are following suite</li>\r\n	<li>Chile: Crowdfunding is a large phenomenon in Latin America; the Chilean economy, what with its focus on innovation and <a href="http://santiagotimes.cl/crowdfunding-takes-chile-energizes-entrepreneurship-region/">entrepreneurship</a>, ideally sets the stage for crowdfunding in the country; while <a href="http://santiagotimes.cl/crowdfunding-takes-chile-energizes-entrepreneurship-region/">some entrepreneurs</a> point out that Chileans may not as yet be as Internet-savvy as they’d need to be in order to embrace crowdfunding, <a href="http://www.universocrowdfunding.com/plataformas-de-crowdfunding-en-latinoamerica/">several platforms</a> already exist within the country</li>\r\n	<li>Turkey: Several <a href="http://fonlabeni.com/">Turkish platforms</a> exist, including Fonlabeni, Fongogo, and Biayda</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<a href="http://thesoholoft.com/global-list-of-crowdfunding-sites/">Other countries</a> with crowdfunding include Germany, Argentina, Norway, Austria, Finland, South Korea, Japan, the Philippines, Ireland, Israel, Portugal, the Czech Republic, the Ukraine, Kenya, Sweden, New Zealand, Estonia, the United Arab Emirates, India, Belgium, Hong Kong, the Russian Federation, and South Africa. (If you’re looking for specific sites, head <a href="http://thesoholoft.com/global-list-of-crowdfunding-sites/">here</a> for a relatively comprehensive list of global crowdfunding platforms!)\r\n\r\nSo, now that we’ve established where in the world you <em>can </em>do equity crowdfunding, where is it impossible? Apparently, Singapore! Despite the fact that Singapore is a huge financial center, crowdfunding platforms still appear to be <a href="http://www.mas.gov.sg/regulations-and-financial-stability/regulations-guidance-and-licensing/securities-futures-and-funds-management/forms/collective-investment-schemes.aspx">illegal</a> in the country.', 'Where in the world can you equity crowdfund?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', 'world-can-equity-crowdfund', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=720', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(721, 10, '2015-05-08 04:57:46', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In order to comprehensively understand equity crowdfunding, it’s important to familiarize oneself with a little bit of e-commerce-related vocabulary.\r\n\r\nVertical portals (also called “<a href="http://searchcio.techtarget.com/definition/vertical-portal">vortals</a>”) are web sites that provide gateways or portals to information related to a particular industry (<em>e.g.</em>, health care, insurance, food manufacturing). These are, in other words, portals to vertical industries, which are industries focused on a relatively narrow range of goods and services (horizontal industries, by contrast, produce a broader range of goods and services).\r\n\r\nVertical portals are relevant to equity crowdfunding because most industries tend to specialize, and thus, tend to be vertical. Vertical portals can thus serve to unite people interested in buying, selling, or exchanging information about a specific subset of topics and products.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://thesoholoft.com/global-list-of-crowdfunding-sites/">Many</a> equity crowdfunding sites currently in existence could be considered vortals, as they often cater to a specific subset of products and services:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Music-related equity crowdfunding sites. France, Belgium, the Netherlands, Mexico, the USA, Canada, and the UK all have crowdfunding portals dedicated specifically to funding musicians. Singers, musicians, and music projects can all find support via pre-orders, capital for covering video production, recording, touring, marketing, merchandising, and any other music-related expenses. Some portals are specifically dedicated to helping new talents find production.</li>\r\n	<li>Visual arts/creative project crowdfunding sites. Mexico, the USA, France, Italy, the Netherlands, Canada, the UK, Australia, Ireland, New Zealand, Spain, Brazil, Argentina, Chile, Germany, Norway, Switzerland, South Korea, and Japan have all looked to endorse creative projects via crowdfunding. Some sites cater specifically to visual arts or non-lucrative projects, while other sites cover all creative projects, including infrastructure for free knowledge and open code.</li>\r\n	<li>Religion-specific crowdfunding sites. Several sites exist catering to Christian and Jewish communities, including 1and700.com and Jcrowd.com, respectively.</li>\r\n	<li>Social project-specific crowdfunding sites. Many crowdfunding sites are geared solely at assisting social projects; platforms include Octopousse.com, Buzzbnk.org, Lets.bt, Startsomegood.com, and Respekt.net</li>\r\n	<li>Student support crowdfunding sites. Several crowdfunding sites exist exclusively to support students: a group with significant needs, given how competitive scholarships have become, and in view of the fact that tuition keeps increasing. China, Canada, the USA, Spain, and France, among others, have built relevant portals. Some portals use peer-to-peer lending to support college students, while others involve students asking their family, friends, and other benefactors to reward them for doing well in their coursework; still others provide scholarships to youth leaders in the developing world, or crowd-fund student loans and classroom projects</li>\r\n	<li>Sports-related crowdfunding sites. Sports-related crowdfunding sites supporting both professional clubs and individual sportsmen and women have emerged across the USA, the UK, and the Netherlands, and across many sports, including baseball, European football/soccer, basketball, American football, and tennis</li>\r\n	<li>Journalism-related crowdfunding sites. Newspapers, reporters, and journalists of all kinds can get support via crowdfunding sites based in France, the USA, Germany, and the Netherlands, among others; some sites support independent journalism, while others support independent projects, e-news websites, and photojournalism specifically</li>\r\n	<li>Book-related crowdfunding sites. The Netherlands, France, the UK, and Canada, among others, support book projects; some sites are specifically dedicated to photo-book projects, while other book-centric sites go so far as to support movie and music projects</li>\r\n	<li>Comics-related crowdfunding sites. As much as comics would seem like a comparatively small market to enter with crowdfunding, comics have their own crowdfunding communities in France and Belgium!</li>\r\n	<li>Fashion-focused crowdfunding sites. The USA and France have embraced fashion-center crowdfunding, with sites primarily supporting selected fashion designers</li>\r\n	<li>Product design- and furniture-centric crowdfunding sites. France, Canada, and the USA, among others, have created crowdfunding sites in support of assorted designers and specific furniture projects; some sites, like Quirky, support any kind of design-driven creative products</li>\r\n	<li>Film-centered crowdfunding sites. France’s crowdfunding community devotes a lot of attention to films, with certain sites supporting solely film production while others cater to investing in distribution</li>\r\n	<li>And yes, even crowdfunding sites that allow you to specifically support… horses?! In France and the UK, you can co-buy a horse for competition!</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nCumulatively, then, vertical crowdfunding portals exist for almost every industry imaginable! Sports, music, fashion, horse-racing… nearly everything has been assimilated into the crowdfunding universe!', 'Fundamental Definitions: Vertical Portals', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-08 04:57:46', '2015-05-08 04:57:46', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=721', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(722, 10, '2015-05-08 05:00:32', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In past articles, we have already elucidated an increasingly obvious fact: equity crowdfunding is becoming a global phenomenon. Opportunities to invest and seek investment exist virtually everywhere, with platforms dotting North America, Latin America, Asia, Europe, and Oceania, and regulation emerging in many locales. Some countries, like the USA, have an incredible number of platforms, stretching into the thousands.\r\n\r\nWith so many equity crowdfunding platforms available, and with alternative investments emerging as an exciting new playing field, entrepreneurs have a lot of choice where selecting the right crowdfunding model and platform for their campaigns is concerned. However, how precisely <em>should </em>entrepreneurs decide which portal is the right one to use?\r\n\r\nAmong other things, it is important to consider which <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/01/61210-crowdfunding-escalator-pick-right-crowdfunding-platform/">business stage</a> your business is currently in.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>If your business is still largely an idea, and you’re in need of very early-stage capital, you may want to turn to either a donation campaign (if you’re mobilizing support from family and friends) or a rewards campaign (if you already have some demand for pre-order of your product or service)</li>\r\n	<li>If your business is already active and operating, it may be wise to go with a predominantly rewards-based campaign: this is well-suited to businesses that need cash flow supplementation and expansion, and particularly those operating in the social venture, film, and hardware spheres</li>\r\n	<li>If your business mostly needs validation of its business model, and has a good credit rating, you may want to consider a lending model: this allows you to pay lower rates than the banks while gathering local investors together; further, equity can still be too expensive at the validation stage of business, given that valuations are not maximized, so lending may be your best option</li>\r\n	<li>If your business is mostly validated, but is seeking expansion and rapid scaling (<em>g.</em>, new locations, increased inventories, more staff, increased capital investment to drive revenue and production), then equity may be the favorable model to go with, as it’ll attract the kind of accredited investors who can ably assist you in growing your business. Debt crowdfunding, traditional bank lending, and angel investment are other options, assuming your business doesn’t need as much marketing, and is seen as a desirable bid</li>\r\n	<li>If your business is relatively mature, and can fund itself from cash flow five years after operation, then your options are, understandably, the most diverse – a range of models may fit your situation</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIt is also important to consider <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/01/61210-crowdfunding-escalator-pick-right-crowdfunding-platform/">which sector</a> you’re operating in! Certain models have shown to be more acceptable for some industries than for others. Rewards-based models, for example, have tended to be very useful for social ventures, technologies, and the arts. Equity works well for start-ups that attract angels, as well as firms at the expansion and maturity stages mentioned above. Lending is particularly good, by contrast, for expansion-phase businesses.\r\n\r\nFinally, of course, it’s important to consider how well your platform of choice <a href="http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2015/01/61210-crowdfunding-escalator-pick-right-crowdfunding-platform/">has performed</a>. Has it generated sufficient funding for past projects? How many projects has it supported; of these, how many have successfully met their goals? Does the executive team appear to be capable and knowledgeable where crowdfunding is concerned? Does the platform directly appeal to your goals? Does it have features that could assist you in marketing? Do you know of any particularly successful businesses that have previously used this platform? All these questions and more are important to answer in selecting the right platform!\r\n\r\nWhile equity crowdfunding itself is very useful, it’s also important to, prior to picking a platform, actually decide if equity crowdfunding is right for you! It’s important to have a solid business model and plan, prepare yourself legally, evaluate a range of platforms, and understand your audience if deciding whether or not this is the move for you right now.', 'How do you select an equity crowdfunding portal?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-08 05:00:32', '2015-05-08 05:00:32', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=722', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(723, 10, '2015-05-08 05:02:46', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '“We’re living in a transformational era for financial services. Our children will look back at these past decades and laugh at how we banked” – Bradley Leimer, Mechanics Bank, California\r\n\r\n“Fintech” or “FinTech”, also known as “financial technology” is comprised of all businesses geared at using software to provide financial services to customers and financial institutions. Fintech companies are typically start-ups geared at modifying how finance is carried out.\r\n\r\nInnovation is being had across <a href="http://www.ndrc.ie/2014/03/fintech/">just about everything</a> in the financial services sector: payments and transactions, mobile banking, trading, commodities markets, FX, peer-to-peer lending and crowdfunding (our favorite!), retail banking, risk and compliance, security and privacy, digital and alternative currencies, digital wallets, financial advisory services, and insurance are all being revitalized by fintech. Excellence in data analytics, cloud computing, and SaaS business models are all enabling this space to prosper more than ever before. Fintech customers can also be just about any business: financial institutions themselves, clients of financial institutions, small businesses, and customers themselves.\r\n\r\nThis industry is rapidly growing, then, with global investment in fintech more than tripling to $3 billion in 2013 from $930 million in 2008. Further, this growth is occurring in a range of locales. In the <a href="http://www.hottopics.ht/stories/fintech/what-is-fintech-and-why-it-matters/">UK</a>, forty percent of London’s workforce, for example, is employed in financial and technology services. In the Asia Pacific region, a new fintech hub is set to be opened in <a href="http://www.afr.com/p/business/financial_services/fintech_heats_up_competition_with_P2CTPJAaAQD1djb3p6BHSO">Sydney, Australia</a> as of spring 2015; several other players already exist in this region. In Hong Kong, specifically, novel <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/tomgroenfeldt/2014/09/02/fintech-innovation-lab-in-hong-kong-launches-with-eight-firms/">innovation labs</a> are being launched to advance fintech. In Toronto, <a href="http://www.marsdd.com/our-sectors/information-and-communications-technology/financial-technology-cluster/">MaRS Discovery District</a> – a not-for-profit corporation eared at commercializing medical research and other technologies – offers fintech start-ups a strategic network of partners, rapid validation, access to investment, product feedback, sales opportunities, and business advisory services. Cumulatively, then, fintech is spreading the world over.\r\n\r\nTo give you a taste of what kinds of businesses fintech incorporates, let’s take a look at some of the fintech-related start-ups that <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/ilyapozin/2014/12/14/15-fintech-startups-to-watch-in-2015/"><em>Forbes</em></a> is hailing as truly transformative in the 2015 fintech space:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>BillGuard: A service geared at alerting users to hidden fees, alerting merchants to fraud, and monitoring one’s spending, BillGuard has both iOS and Android interfaces, and has helped save users detect over $60 million in suspect transactions</li>\r\n	<li>OnDeck: An alternative small-business lender, OnDeck uses a different method to evaluate creditworthiness than banks, and can process loans within a day</li>\r\n	<li>Wealthfront: A company involved in the automated financial advisory space that has amassed more than $1 billion for its proprietary algorithms</li>\r\n	<li>The Currency Cloud: An internationally successful start-up, The Currency Cloud seeks to help small businesses in international payments, and is rapidly gaining market share</li>\r\n	<li>Stripe: A company that’s helped the likes of Twitter and Alibaba support mobile and e-commerce payments</li>\r\n	<li>Epiphyte: A Bitcoin- and crypto-currency-centered company, Epiphyte provides software and consulting to help banks legally deal with these technologies</li>\r\n	<li>AstroPay: A cross-border payment services provider in Latin America and China, this company seeks to reduce fraud by helping merchants monitor payments in high-fraud areas</li>\r\n	<li>Banking Up: A prepaid debit card for people who don’t have access to standard banking that has expanded to help financial institutions offer customers branded accounts</li>\r\n	<li>Tipalti: An SaaS technology that simplifies mass payment, allowing people to transfer money to payees anywhere in the world <em>en masse</em>; this company has seen noteworthy clients (<em>g.</em>, Disqus), and complies with local regulations</li>\r\n	<li>Flint: A mobile payments processing system geared at freeing people from desktop-based systems and associated set-up fees; this app. directly utilizes device cameras to scan credit and debit cards, so no excess hardware is required; in its latest round, this company raised $6 million in funding</li>\r\n	<li>Square: Similar to Flint, Square was the first to solve the problem of processing credit card payments at points of sale – essentially, Square equips us all with a mobile-compatible credit card reader; as of December 2014, the company was valued at $6 billion</li>\r\n	<li>Check: Check is geared predominantly at helping users make mobile bill payments; it consolidates users’ bills in one app., and also assists us in avoiding late fees; as of May 2014, Check has been acquired by Intuit</li>\r\n	<li>Zipmark: A company that enables payments by “digital check”, processing check payments online and overnight – while this platform was previously geared mostly at small businesses, larger ones are now adopting it</li>\r\n	<li>WePay: Receiving backing from the ever-famous Y Combinator, WePay seeks to make online payments for platforms much easier; specifically, the site enables platforms like crowdfunding sites to collect payments from many customers and give them to a smaller group of merchants; the customer</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCumulatively, then, fintech is a truly booming industry that appears to be thoroughly revitalizing the financial services sector, and is thus integral to understand in approaching crowdfunding. For further information, should you be interested, Accenture has created a comprehensive report outlining the rise of fintech, which is available <a href="http://www.accenture.com/SiteCollectionDocuments/PDF/Accenture-Rise-of-Fintech-New-York.pdf">here</a>.', 'Fundamental Definitions: Fintech', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-08 05:02:46', '2015-05-08 05:02:46', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=723', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(724, 10, '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In reading about regulated equity crowdfunding, you may have heard the abbreviation “EMD”, and wondered what this acronym concerns. Alternatively, you may know what an EMD is, and may be interested in how working with an EMD can benefit your company, both in general and where regulated equity crowdfunding is concerned.\r\n\r\nTo begin, a quick introduction!\r\n\r\nAn “EMD”, or “<a href="http://www.pcmacanada.com/?page=exemptmarketdealers">exempt market dealer</a>” is an exempt market securities dealer registered under provincial securities legislation in one or more jurisdictions of Canada. Specifically, an EMD is a group of registered personnel, all of whom are experts in exempt market securities.  Firstly, it can be a dealer or underwriter for any securities that are prospectus exempt. Secondly, it can also be a dealer for any securities that are prospectus qualified or prospectus exempt, assuming the relevant client is qualified to purchase prospectus exempt securities.\r\n\r\nEMDs undergo a registration process with one or more securities regulatory authorities in Canada (<em>e.g.</em>, principal regulators, SROs), the likes of which we will discuss in a later article. (Edit: This later article is now available! To find out more about the EMD registration process, please consider reading “How do you become an exempt market dealer (EMD)?”)\r\n\r\nEMDs are also distinct from other categories of securities dealers (<em>e.g.</em>, investment dealers, mutual fund dealers, scholarship plan dealers, and restricted dealers), and are considerably less restricted than all of the aforementioned types. While, for example, investment dealers are required to be members of the Investment Industry Regulatory Organization of Canada (IIROC), this is not a requirement for EMDs. Similarly, while mutual fund dealers are restricted to dealing in prospectus qualified mutual funds and need to be members of the Mutual Funds Dealers Association of Canada (MFDA), these are not necessary requirements for EMDs. Scholarship plan dealers are restricted to solely scholarship plans and educational trusts, and restricted dealers work only with particular products; neither of these restrictions hold for EMDs.\r\n\r\nSo, why work with an EMD, though? What precisely is it that makes an EMD useful for an organization, besides their ability to deal with many different securities?\r\n\r\nRealistically, nearly everyone – from owner-operated companies to established public and private companies – can <a href="http://www.pcmacanada.com/?page=exemptmarketdealers">benefit</a> from the expertise of an EMD, and consulting one can be advantageous for a few reasons.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>For one, EMDs make for legal security. In Canada, for example, they are governed by regulatory and compliance standards that are set by bodies like the Ontario Securities Commission</li>\r\n	<li>Working with an EMD may also grant you increased peace of mind, as, once again, EMDs must adhere to certain stringent standards set by a regulating body</li>\r\n	<li>EMDs are also proficient where securities dealing is concerned, as they must pass a set of examinations that test their financial management knowledge, must maintain certain minima where levels of capital and insurance are concerned, and must file audited financial statements</li>\r\n	<li>Because EMDs are governed by regulation and must earn a license, and because they are subject to certain capital and proficiency requirements, you’ll get the best possible practices you could out of your experience</li>\r\n	<li>EMDs also have broader capabilities than other dealers, given that they can be experts in the sale and purchase of essentially any security, prospectus exempt or prospectus qualified, and their services are available across a range of industries</li>\r\n	<li>Finally, if an issue arises with a financial adviser who is an EMD, then there is an independent dispute-resolution option available; this, again, ensures that working with an EMD is the best possible experience it can be, and that everyone involved is held accountable for their professionalism</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCumulatively, then, there are many reasons to work with an EMD: just the fact that EMDs must adhere to regulation and pass qualifying tests makes for increased reliability, which is essential to the kind of advice necessary in regulated equity crowdfunding.', 'What is an EMD, and what is the value of an EMD in regulated equity crowdfunding?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', 'emd-value-emd-regulated-equity-crowdfunding', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=724', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(725, 10, '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In a prior article, we discussed what an exempt market dealer (EMD) is, and how he or she may be beneficial in regulated equity crowdfunding. Here, let’s get straight to the point, and explore how an everyday individual can become an EMD.\r\n\r\nTo quickly sum up: an EMD is an exempt market securities dealer registered under provincial legislation in Canada; regardless of your province, the regulatory framework for EMDs is the same, and is set out in National Instrument 31-103 <em>Registration Requirements, Exemptions and Ongoing Registrant Obligations</em>. EMDs primarily play two roles in capital markets. They can, firstly, act as underwriters or dealers for securities which are prospectus exempt. Secondly, they can deal any securities (including those which are prospectus qualified, assuming that the clients in question legally qualify for purchase of exempt securities (qualification criteria can be found in National Instrument 45-106 <em>Prospectus and Registration Exemptions</em>, and also hold for the whole of Canada).\r\n\r\nAs mentioned, EMDs are different from investment dealers, mutual fund dealers, scholarship plan dealers, and restricted dealers. While each category of security dealer has its own benefits, we’re assuming in this article that you already know you want to become an EMD. Now, all that’s left to do is find out how…\r\n\r\nIn order to become an EMD, you must, broadly, register as an EMD with one or more securities regulatory authorities in Canada! We can break this process down into several steps:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Read the whole of <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/documents/en/Securities-Category3/rule_20090717_31-103_national-instrument.pdf">National Instrument 31-103</a>, and Part Three of <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/documents/en/Securities-Category3/rule_20090717_33-109_schedule-a.pdf">National Instrument 33-109</a>.</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure the whole of your firm is interested in registering as an exempt market dealer. Whole firms are required to register as EMDs before any individuals affiliated with a firm can become relevantly registered.</li>\r\n	<li>To register a whole firm, fill out <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/documents/en/Securities-Category3/form_33-109f6.pdf">Form 33-109F6 (Firm Registration)</a>. If you don’t understand appropriate terminology, consult the aforementioned National Instruments (NIs), namely 31-103 and 33-109, as well as relevant sections of NIs <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/en/14882.htm">14-101</a> and <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/en/13530.htm">52-107</a>. Make sure you read the “Definitions” section of the Firm Registration form, as this can be helpful in elucidating terminology.</li>\r\n	<li>Find one or more individuals interested in being dealing representatives. You can find a further description of this role, its requirements, and its responsibilities in <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/documents/en/Securities-Category3/rule_20090717_31-103_national-instrument.pdf">NI 31-103</a>.</li>\r\n	<li>Find a chief compliance officer (CCO). You can find a further description of this role, its requirements, and its responsibilities in <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/documents/en/Securities-Category3/rule_20090717_31-103_national-instrument.pdf">NI 31-103</a>.</li>\r\n	<li>Find an ultimate designated person. You can find a further description of this role, its requirements, and its responsibilities in <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/documents/en/Securities-Category3/rule_20090717_31-103_national-instrument.pdf">NI 31-103</a>.</li>\r\n	<li>To register each of 3), 4), and 5), make sure that each individual has the necessary qualifications and proficiency requirements for the position. A chief compliance officer (CCO), for example, must have passed the Canadian Investment Funds Exam, the Canadian Securities Course Exam, the Investment Funds in Canada Course Exam, the PDO Exam, or the Mutual Funds Dealers Compliance Exam, or must meet other requirements. Information about these requirements can, again, be found in NI 31-103.</li>\r\n	<li>Once qualifications for 3), 4), and 5) are verified, fill out <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/documents/en/Securities-Category3/form_33-109f4.pdf">Form 33-109F4 (Individual Registration)</a> <em>per each individual</em>. Even if this individual is applying to be registered in several categories, one form per person will do.</li>\r\n	<li>Submit the Firm Registration form to a principal regulator or relevant self-regulatory organization (SRO), either via e-mail or in person. You can find relevant contact information in Appendix B of <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/documents/en/Securities-Category3/rule_20090717_33-109_schedule-b.pdf">Companion Policy 33-109CP <em>Registration Information</em></a>.</li>\r\n	<li>Submit the Individual Registration form at the National Registration Database (NRD) website in NRD format at <a href="http://www.nrd.ca">nrd.ca</a>, or, if you’re relying on the temporary hardship exemption discussed in Section 5.1 of NI 31-102, in a different format to a principal regulator/SRO. If you need help with what you should be doing when filling out this paperwork, contact your sponsoring firm, or a legal adviser who’s comfortable with securities law.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nA few excess notes concerning the Firm Registration form (Form 33-109F6):\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>There are supporting documents involved, namely: a business plan, policies and procedures manual, client agreements, constating documents, organization chart, ownership chart, calculation of excess working capital, directors’ resolution approving insurance, audited financial statements, letter of direction to auditors, and Schedule B. Details about all these documents can be found within the form itself, available <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/documents/en/Securities-Category3/form_33-109f6.pdf">here</a></li>\r\n	<li>You will need to continually update regulators over time – more details on that are present in Part Three of NI 33-109</li>\r\n	<li>On restricted dealers: If you’re looking for registration in more than one jurisdiction or Canada or category, other than in the category of restricted dealer, complete and submit just one form. If you are looking to be a restricted dealer, submit and file the form with each jurisdiction of Canada where you’re seeking to be a restricted dealer</li>\r\n	<li>On Ontario: If you’re seeking registration in Ontario, but Ontario is not your firm’s principal regulator, file a copy of this form without supporting documents</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nA few excess notes concerning the Individual Registration form (Form 33-109F4):\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>You need to have quite a bit of information on hand to fill out this documentation! Make sure to check what’s needed ahead of time</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf you’re looking to find out which other forms you may need, or need help understanding this paperwork, refer to the <a href="http://www.osc.gov.on.ca/documents/en/Dealers/da_20100409_guide-reg-forms.pdf">OSC Guide to Registration Forms</a>. This section should tell you all you need to know about filing EMD paperwork!', 'How do you become an exempt market dealer (EMD)?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', 'become-exempt-market-dealer-emd', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=725', 0, 'post', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(726, 10, '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In our last two articles, we centered on the exempt market dealer (EMD) designation, and discussed both the process inherent to becoming an EMD, and the benefits that working with an EMD may bring to essentially any company.\r\n\r\nIf you read “How do you become an exempt market dealer?”, you’ll know that registering an EMD requires the participation of one or more dealing representatives, one ultimate designated person, and one chief compliance officer (CCO). While the dealing representatives act as dealers or underwriters with respect to securities, the ultimate designated person supervises the activities of the firm, ensuring compliance with securities legislation by the firm as a whole and by each individual, and also promotes compliance by the firm and its individuals. The chief compliance officer (CCO), meanwhile, is responsible for most of the executive work involved in running an EMD. He or she establishes and maintains policies and procedures for assessing compliance with securities legislation (both by the firm and by the individuals acting on its behalf), monitors compliance on a routine basis, and reports to the ultimate designated person of the firm if any circumstances are in non-compliance with the relevant legislation. The chief compliance officer (CCO) is also responsible for an annual report to the firm’s board of directors that assesses compliance of the firm and its affiliated individuals.\r\n\r\nSo, who can be a chief compliance officer (CCO), and how can a person become one?\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The CCO must, firstly, be either an officer or partner of a registered firm, or its sole proprietor.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol start="2">\r\n	<li>Assuming this criterion is met, the potential CCO must then:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Pass the PDO Exam and the Canadian Securities Course Exam, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n	<li>Pass the PDO Exam and the Exempt Market Products Exam, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n	<li>Meet the requirements of a portfolio manager’s chief compliance officer, namely:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Earned a CFA Charter or professional designation as a lawyer, Chartered Accountant, Certified General Accountant, or Certified Management Accountant in some jurisdiction of Canada, a notary in Quebec, or the equivalent in a foreign jurisdiction, passed the Canadian Securities Course Exam and the PDO Exam, and gained thirty-six months of relevant securities experience while working at an investment dealer, a registered adviser, or an investment fund manager, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n	<li>Earned a CFA Charter or professional designation as a lawyer, Chartered Accountant, Certified General Accountant, or Certified Management Accountant in some jurisdiction of Canada, a notary in Quebec, or the equivalent in a foreign jurisdiction, passed the Canadian Securities Course Exam and the PDO Exam, and provided professional services in the securities industry for thirty-six months and worked at a registered dealer, registered adviser, or investment fund manager for three months, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Pass the Canadian Securities Course Exam and the PDO Exam and have worked at an investment dealer or a registered adviser for five years, including for thirty-six months in a compliance capacity, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Pass the Canadian Securities Course Exam and the PDO Exam and have worked for five years at a Canadian financial institution in a compliance capacity pertaining to portfolio management and worked at a registered dealer or a registered adviser for twelve months, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n	<li>Pass the PDO Exam and meet the requirements a portfolio manager’s advising representative, namely:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Earn a CFA Charter and have twelve months of relevant investment management experience in the thirty-six month period before applying for registration, <em>or</em>;</li>\r\n	<li>Receive a Canadian Investment Manager designation, have forty-eight months of relevant investment management experience, twelve months of which was in the thirty-six month period before applying for registration</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol start="3">\r\n	<li>If the relevant criteria are met, the potential CCO may register as a CCO by filling in <a href="https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/documents/en/Securities-Category3/form_33-109f4.pdf">Form 33-109F4 (Individual Registration)</a>, and submitting it at either the National Registration Database (NRD) website in NRD format at <a href="http://www.nrd.ca">nrd.ca</a>, or, if relying on the temporary hardship exemption discussed in Section 5.1 of NI 31-102, in a different format to a principal regulator/SRO. If you are a potential CCO, and need help with what you should be doing when filling out this paperwork, contact your sponsoring firm, or a legal adviser who’s comfortable with securities law.</li>\r\n</ol>', 'What do you need to be a CCO for an EMD?', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', 'need-cco-emd', '', '', '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '2015-05-11 07:27:22', '', 0, 'http://koreconx.com/?p=726', 0, 'post', '', 0),
